{"title_page": "Real Time Crime Center", "text_new": "{{news release|1=article|date=October 2015}}\n[[Image:Realtimecrimecenterofficial.png|thumb|Real Time Crime Center emblem]]\n\nThe '''Real Time Crime Center''' ('''RTCC''') is a centralized technology utilized by law enforcement and emergency first responders. During early adoption, the primary purpose of RTCC was to give field officers and detectives instant information to help identify patterns and stop emerging crime. With emerging cloud-based technology, Real Time Crime Centers in the Cloud have evolved to afford enhanced visibility, unified awareness, and the appropriate force of response in emergency resource deployment. Technological advances in RTCC seeks to continually improve emergency response times in the form of instant-live video, live feed camera docking, virtual incident location mapping and full integration with computer-aided-dispatch ([[Computer-aided dispatch|CAD]]).   \n\nPolice departments that have Real Time Crime Centers, include the [[New York Police Department]], [[Miami-Dade Police Department]], [[Seattle Police Department]], [[Fort Worth Police Department]], [[Metropolitan Police Department, City of St. Louis]], [[Albuquerque Police Department]], [[Austin Police Department]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rangel|first=Leslie|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/crime/how-police-monitors-situations-in-downtown-austin-in-realtime_20180316013018707/1049643246|title=How police monitors situations in downtown Austin in realtime|date=2016-08-02|work=KXAN|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>, [[Tampa Police Department]], [[Minneapolis Police Department]] and [[Houston Police Department]].<ref>[http://abclocal.go.com/ktrk/story?section=news/in_focus&id=7642890 HPD's High-tech center helping solve crimes]</ref> \n\n\n'''Early Adoption'''\n\nThe NYPD RTCC opened on July 18, 2005 and provides support 24/7. The center was built at a cost of $11 million. The information in the center is available to the 37,000 police officers of the [[New York City Police Department]].  The RTCC was funded in part by grants from the non-profit [[New York City Police Foundation]].<ref>*[http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?&aid=52142 NYPD Unveils High-Tech Real Time Crime Center At Police Headquarters]\n*[http://www.gcn.com/print/24_29/37061-1.html Real-time crime fighting comes to Gotham]\n</ref>\n\nRTCC data sources include a data warehouse in which billions of records are made available to detectives and other officers within minutes, instead of days or weeks. These include:<ref>\n*[http://policechiefmagazine.org/magazine/index.cfm?fuseaction=display&article_id=995&issue_id=92006 Stopping Crime in Real Time]\n*[http://www.informationweek.com/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=166401859  New York's Techno Crime Fighters]\n*[https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,1895,1863497,00.asp Fighting Crime in Real Time]\n</ref>\n*More than 5 million New York State criminal records, parole and probation files,\n*More than 20 million New York City criminal complaints, arrests, 911/311 calls and summonses spanning five years,\n*More than 31 million national crime records,\n*More than 33 billion public records.\n\nThe Crime Center employs satellite imaging and mapping of New York City (using [[Geographic Information System]] software) precinct-by-precinct. The link analysis capacity of the RTCC can track suspects to their known addresses and point detectives to the locations where they are most likely to flee. The Real Time Crime Center was built with the oversight of provider [[Dimension Data]].<br />\n<br />\n'''Emerging Cloud-Based Technology and Innovation'''\n\nReal Time Crime Center (RTCC) in the Cloud are centralized technology platforms which extracts and unifies live video and data feeds from virtually any source, creating a central hub that enhances the situational awareness and investigative capabilities of law enforcement and public safety agencies. \n\nOn April 1, 2020, the Minneapolis Police Department's Strategic Information Center (SIC) announced a partnership with, [https://www.fusus.com/ F\u016bsus], to activate a ground-breaking law enforcement platform, [https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone f\u016bsusONE], which will be live and fully operational on April 16th, 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform|title=MPD to activiate Fusus Real Time Crime Center Platform|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n<br />\n<br />\n''\"We\u2019ve worked closely with the Fusus team to help create a real-time crime center solution that truly meets the day-to-day intelligence needs of our department,\u201d said Commander Scott Gerlicher of the MPD\u2019s Special Operation and Intelligence Division. \u201c[https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform The activation of the Fusus platform] represents a significant step forward not just for the MPD's crime mitigation and public safety efforts, but for law enforcement technology in general. With the Fusus platform in place, the MPD will be one of the first Police Departments in the nation to be leveraging a real-time crime center in the cloud solution.\u201d''\n<br />\n<br />\n'''The F\u016bsus Unified Awareness Platform will bring the following capabilities to the MPD\u2019s SIC:''' \n\n*Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD) Integration -along with video correlation to Priority 1 locations\n*Integration to Minneapolis 911 dispatch\n*Live video from the Minneapolis Downtown Improvement District area\n*Community Camera Registry Location Data\n*Live Cell Phone Video during an ongoing incident\n*Live Video from Stadiums and other Community Owned Video Sources\n*ShotSpotter Gunfire Detection Integration\n*Mutual Aid with other law enforcement agencies\n*Community shared video and photo for Tips via SMS-Text\n*f\u016bsusALERT Panic App integration for(policy-based) video sharing on alert\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fusuops f\u016bsusOPS] Officer Locations, Text Communications,and Team Coordination for Incident Management\n*\u00a0Floor plan Integrations to Locations of Interest\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.nycpolicefoundation.org/ New York City Police Foundation official site]\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone F\u016bsus - Real Time Crime Center in the Cloud]\n{{New York City Police Department}}\n[[Category:New York City Police Department]]\n{{police-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{news release|1=article|date=October 2015}}\n[[Image:Realtimecrimecenterofficial.png|thumb|Real Time Crime Center emblem]]\n\nThe '''Real Time Crime Center''' ('''RTCC''') is a centralized technology utilized by law enforcement and emergency first responders. During early adoption, the primary purpose of RTCC was to give field officers and detectives instant information to help identify patterns and stop emerging crime. With emerging cloud-based technology, Real Time Crime Centers in the Cloud have evolved to afford enhanced visibility, unified awareness, and the appropriate force of response in emergency resource deployment. Technological advances in RTCC seek to continually improve emergency response times in the form of instant-live video, live feed camera docking, virtual incident location mapping and full integration with computer-aided-dispatch ([[Computer-aided dispatch|CAD]]).   \n\nPolice departments that have Real Time Crime Centers, include the [[New York Police Department]], [[Miami-Dade Police Department]], [[Seattle Police Department]], [[Fort Worth Police Department]], [[Metropolitan Police Department, City of St. Louis]], [[Albuquerque Police Department]], [[Austin Police Department]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rangel|first=Leslie|url=https://www.kxan.com/news/crime/how-police-monitors-situations-in-downtown-austin-in-realtime_20180316013018707/1049643246|title=How police monitors situations in downtown Austin in realtime|date=2016-08-02|work=KXAN|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>, [[Tampa Police Department]], [[Minneapolis Police Department]] and [[Houston Police Department]].<ref>[http://abclocal.go.com/ktrk/story?section=news/in_focus&id=7642890 HPD's High-tech center helping solve crimes]</ref> \n\n\n'''Early Adoption'''\n\nThe NYPD RTCC opened on July 18, 2005 and provides support 24/7. The center was built at a cost of $11 million. The information in the center is available to the 37,000 police officers of the [[New York City Police Department]].  The RTCC was funded in part by grants from the non-profit [[New York City Police Foundation]].<ref>*[http://www.ny1.com/ny1/content/index.jsp?&aid=52142 NYPD Unveils High-Tech Real Time Crime Center At Police Headquarters]\n*[http://www.gcn.com/print/24_29/37061-1.html Real-time crime fighting comes to Gotham]\n</ref>\n\nRTCC data sources include a data warehouse in which billions of records are made available to detectives and other officers within minutes, instead of days or weeks. These include:<ref>\n*[http://policechiefmagazine.org/magazine/index.cfm?fuseaction=display&article_id=995&issue_id=92006 Stopping Crime in Real Time]\n*[http://www.informationweek.com/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=166401859  New York's Techno Crime Fighters]\n*[https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,1895,1863497,00.asp Fighting Crime in Real Time]\n</ref>\n*More than 5 million New York State criminal records, parole and probation files,\n*More than 20 million New York City criminal complaints, arrests, 911/311 calls and summonses spanning five years,\n*More than 31 million national crime records,\n*More than 33 billion public records.\n\nThe Crime Center employs satellite imaging and mapping of New York City (using [[Geographic Information System]] software) precinct-by-precinct. The link analysis capacity of the RTCC can track suspects to their known addresses and point detectives to the locations where they are most likely to flee. The Real Time Crime Center was built with the oversight of provider [[Dimension Data]].<br />\n<br />\n'''Emerging Cloud-Based Technology and Innovation'''\n\nReal Time Crime Center (RTCC) in the Cloud are centralized technology platforms which extracts and unifies live video and data feeds from virtually any source, creating a central hub that enhances the situational awareness and investigative capabilities of law enforcement and public safety agencies. \n\nOn April 1, 2020, the Minneapolis Police Department's Strategic Information Center (SIC) announced a partnership with, [https://www.fusus.com/ F\u016bsus], to activate a ground-breaking law enforcement platform, [https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone f\u016bsusONE], which will be live and fully operational on April 16th, 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform|title=MPD to activiate Fusus Real Time Crime Center Platform|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n<br />\n<br />\n''\"We\u2019ve worked closely with the Fusus team to help create a real-time crime center solution that truly meets the day-to-day intelligence needs of our department,\u201d said Commander Scott Gerlicher of the MPD\u2019s Special Operation and Intelligence Division. \u201c[https://www.fusus.com/blog/press-release-minneapolis-police-department-to-activate-fusus-real-time-crime-center-platform The activation of the Fusus platform] represents a significant step forward not just for the MPD's crime mitigation and public safety efforts, but for law enforcement technology in general. With the Fusus platform in place, the MPD will be one of the first Police Departments in the nation to be leveraging a real-time crime center in the cloud solution.\u201d''\n<br />\n<br />\n'''The F\u016bsus Unified Awareness Platform will bring the following capabilities to the MPD\u2019s SIC:''' \n\n*Computer Aided Dispatch (CAD) Integration -along with video correlation to Priority 1 locations\n*Integration to Minneapolis 911 dispatch\n*Live video from the Minneapolis Downtown Improvement District area\n*Community Camera Registry Location Data\n*Live Cell Phone Video during an ongoing incident\n*Live Video from Stadiums and other Community Owned Video Sources\n*ShotSpotter Gunfire Detection Integration\n*Mutual Aid with other law enforcement agencies\n*Community shared video and photo for Tips via SMS-Text\n*f\u016bsusALERT Panic App integration for(policy-based) video sharing on alert\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fusuops f\u016bsusOPS] Officer Locations, Text Communications,and Team Coordination for Incident Management\n*\u00a0Floor plan Integrations to Locations of Interest\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.nycpolicefoundation.org/ New York City Police Foundation official site]\n*[https://www.fusus.com/products/fususone F\u016bsus - Real Time Crime Center in the Cloud]\n{{New York City Police Department}}\n[[Category:New York City Police Department]]\n{{police-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Appleseed1492", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_Time_Crime_Center"}
{"title_page": "N,N-diethylmethylamine", "text_new": "{{short description|Organic compound, industrial chemical}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{Orphan|date=February 2020}}}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''N'',''N''-diethylmethylamine}}\n{{chembox\n| Name           = ''N'',''N''-diethylmethylamine\n| ImageFile      = Diethylmethylamine.png\n| OtherNames     = \n| IUPACName      = ''N''-ethyl-''N''-methylethanamine\n| PIN            = ''N'',''N''-Diethylmethylamine\n| SystematicName = \n| Section1       = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CASNo=616-39-7\n| ChEMBL = 2448813\n| EINECS=210-480-5\n| PubChem=12022\n| ChemSpiderID = 11527\n| StdInChI=1S/C5H13N/c1-4-6(3)5-2/h4-5H2,1-3H3\n| StdInChIKey = GNVRJGIVDSQCOP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| SMILES = CCN(C)CC\n  }}\n| Section2       = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=5 | H=13 | N=1\n| Appearance=Volatile liquid at room temp.\n| Density= 0.72 g/mL\n| MeltingPtC=-196.0\n| BoilingPtC= 66.0\n| Solubility=310.5 g/L\n| pKa = 10.35 (for the conjugate acid) (H<sub>2</sub>O)\n  }}\n| Section3       = {{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards=acute toxicity\n| FlashPtF=-11\n| AutoignitionPt =\n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS02}}{{GHS05}}{{GHS06}}{{GHS07}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Danger\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|225|301|314|332}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|210|233|240|241|242|243|260|261|264|270|271|280|301+310|301+330+331|303+361+353|304+312|304+340|305+351+338|310|312|321|330|363|370+378|403+235|405|501}}\n  }}\n| Section4       = \n| Section5       = \n| Section6       = \n| Watchedfields  = \n| verifiedrevid  = \n}}\n\n'''''N'',''N''-diethylmethylamine (diethylmethylamine, DEMA)''' is a [[tertiary amine]] with the formula C<sub>5</sub>H<sub>13</sub>N. ''N'',''N''-Diethylmethylamine is a clear, colorless to pale yellow liquid at room temperature, and is used in various industrial and scientific applications including water desalination as well as analytical and organic chemistry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zafarani-Moattar|first=Mohammed Taghi|last2=Nikjoo|first2=Dariush|date=2008-11-13|title=Liquid\u2212Liquid and Liquid\u2212Liquid\u2212Solid Equilibrium of the Poly(ethylene glycol) Dimethyl Ether 2000 + Sodium Sulfate + Water System|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/je8005858|journal=Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data|language=en|volume=53|issue=11|pages=2666\u20132670|doi=10.1021/je8005858|issn=0021-9568}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ting|first=Andrew M.|last2=Lynn|first2=Scott|last3=Prausnitz|first3=John M.|date=1 April 1992|title=Liquid-liquid equilibria for aqueous systems containing N,N-diethylmethylamine and sodium chloride or sodium sulfate|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/je00006a032|journal=Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data|language=en|volume=37|issue=2|pages=252\u2013259|doi=10.1021/je00006a032|issn=0021-9568|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Lihua|last2=Gough|first2=P. Clayton|last3=DeFelippis|first3=Michael R.|date=2009-01-15|title=Characterization of Poly(ethylene glycol) and PEGylated Products by LC/MS with Postcolumn Addition of Amines|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/ac801711u|journal=Analytical Chemistry|language=en|volume=81|issue=2|pages=567\u2013577|doi=10.1021/ac801711u|issn=0003-2700}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rohlfs|first=R. J.|last2=Hille|first2=R.|date=1994-12-09|title=The reaction of trimethylamine dehydrogenase with diethylmethylamine|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7983019|journal=The Journal of Biological Chemistry|volume=269|issue=49|pages=30869\u201330879|issn=0021-9258|pmid=7983019}}</ref>\n\nDiethylmethylamine is an acute oral and inhalation toxin although limits determining acute and chronic toxicity have not been determined, nor have the acute or chronic effects on various organ systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datasheets.scbt.com/sds/aghs/en/sc-236115.pdf|title=SantaCruz Biotechnology, Inc. Material Safety Data Sheet: N,N-diethylmethylamine|last=|first=|date=27 September 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Additionally, the effects of environmental exposure or accumulation are not currently known.\n\nDEMA can be converted to [[Nitrosation|nitrosated]] to its corresponding [[nitrosamine]] which may present health considerations if DEMA is used in an industrial process that involves nitrating agents at low pH or high temperatures.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nitrosation of volatile amines at the workplace [MAK Value Documentation, 1990]|date=2012|url=https://www.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/3527600418.mb0b03e0001|work=The MAK-Collection for Occupational Health and Safety|pages=24\u201337|publisher=American Cancer Society|language=en|doi=10.1002/3527600418.mb0b03e0001|isbn=978-3-527-60041-0|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/health/scientific_committees/consumer_safety/docs/sccs_o_090.pdf|title=Opinion on Nitrosamines and Secondary Amines in Cosmetic Products|last=|first=|date=27 March 2012|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The nitrosamine [[N-Nitrosodiethylamine|N-nitroso-diethylamine]] has been found in cosmetics and is a possible product of DEMA nitrosation.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, this toxic nitrosamine has only rarely been identified in cosmetic products.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are no specific storage requirements for DEMA, other than the usual precautions for storing a flammable liquid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datasheets.scbt.com/sc-236115.pdf|title=N,N-Diethylmethylamine|last=|first=|date=|website=Santa Cruz Biotechnology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== Preparation ==\nDiethylmethylamine can be produced by [[reductive amination]] of the secondary amine [[Diethylamine|N,N-diethylamine]], in particular under [[Eschweiler\u2013Clarke reaction|Eschweiler-Clarke]] conditions, or by the catalyzed reaction between ethylamine and methanol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.organic-chemistry.org/namedreactions/eschweiler-clarke-reaction.shtm|title=Eschweiler-Clarke Reaction|website=www.organic-chemistry.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Pouilloux|first=Y.|title=Synthesis of dimethylethylamine from ethylamine and methanol over copper catalysts|date=1997-01-01|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167299197808981|work=Studies in Surface Science and Catalysis|volume=108|pages=139\u2013147|editor-last=Blaser|editor-first=H. U.|series=Heterogeneous Catalysis and Fine Chemicals IV|publisher=Elsevier|language=en|doi=10.1016/s0167-2991(97)80898-1|access-date=2020-04-12|last2=Doidy|first2=V.|last3=Hub|first3=S.|last4=Kervennal|first4=J.|last5=Barrault|first5=J.|editor2-last=Baiker|editor2-first=A.|editor3-last=Prins|editor3-first=R.}}</ref> A 1960 patent reports the synthesis of DEMA using [[Methyl p-toluate|methyl toluate]] and [[diethylamine]], but low yields and difficult reaction conditions make this approach infeasible for most synthetic applications.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Class|first=J.B.|title=Production of diethylemthylamine|publisher=United States Patent Office|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Properties ==\n===Molecular structure and conformation===\nThe methylene carbon-nitrogen sigma bonds in DEMA allow for multiple molecular conformations to exist, which has been studied by Bushweller et al. and, more recently, Takeuchi et al. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crocker|first=Christopher|last2=Goggin|first2=Peter L.|date=1978|title=Infrared and Raman spectroscopic studies of conformations in liquid and solid triethyl-, diethyl(methyl)- and ethyldimethyl-amines, -phosphines, and -arsines|url=http://xlink.rsc.org/?DOI=dt9780000388|journal=Journal of the Chemical Society, Dalton Transactions|language=en|issue=5|pages=388|doi=10.1039/dt9780000388|issn=0300-9246}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bushweller|first=C. Hackett|last2=Fleischman|first2=Stephen H.|last3=Grady|first3=Gilbert L.|last4=McGoff|first4=Paul|last5=Rithner|first5=Christopher D.|last6=Whalon|first6=Michael R.|last7=Brennan|first7=John G.|last8=Marcantonio|first8=Richard P.|last9=Dominigue|first9=Raymond P.|date=1982-11|title=Stereodynamics of diethylmethylamine and triethylamine|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/ja00387a012|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=104|issue=23|pages=6224\u20136236|doi=10.1021/ja00387a012|issn=0002-7863}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Takeuchi|first=Hiroshi|last2=Ito|first2=Masaki|last3=Egawa|first3=Toru|date=2007-09|title=Molecular structure and conformation of diethylmethylamine determined by gas electron diffraction and vibrational spectroscopy combined with theoretical calculations|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0022286006008945|journal=Journal of Molecular Structure|language=en|volume=840|issue=1-3|pages=107\u2013113|doi=10.1016/j.molstruc.2006.11.027}}</ref> These studies demonstrated the existence of four major [[Conformational isomerism|conformers]], with the ''trans-trans'' conformer possessing the greatest stability. Additional conformers were shown to exist, but represent a non-significant percentage of the conformer population at any given time and were only observed at low temperatures. Finally, pyramidal [[Pyramidal inversion|inversion]] at the nitrogen atom occurs, as shown by decoelescence of the N-CH<sub>2</sub> resonance in NMR samples that were taken at various decreasing temperatures. The data obtained in these experiments agree with data from the similar tertiary amine [[triethylamine]], leading the authors to conclude that any acyclic trialkylamine with straight-chain moieties will have similar stereodynamics compared to DEMA and triethylamine.\n\n== Usage ==\nDEMA has found use in multiple fields of study including [[nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy]] (NMR), industrial extraction techniques, and water desalination.\n\n=== Lineshape standard of nuclear magnetic resonance experiment ===\nFor a [[Carbon-13 nuclear magnetic resonance|<sup>13</sup>C NMR]] experiment, peak shape and instrument sensitivity are important considerations, and these can be optimized by adjusting the magnetic [[Shim (magnetism)|shims]] to enhance the [[magnetic field]] homogeneity and optimize peak shape. Samples used to optimize peak shape often fail at low temperatures due to peak broadening. However, DEMA has been shown to be a useful lineshape standard at temperatures down to 140K, due to its low melting point of 130K and liquid state at standard temperature and pressure. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fritzsching|first=Keith J.|last2=Itin|first2=Boris|last3=McDermott|first3=Ann E.|date=2018-02-21|title=N,N-Diethylmethylamine as lineshape standard for NMR above 130\u202fK|journal=Journal of Magnetic Resonance|volume=287|pages=110\u2013112|doi=10.1016/j.jmr.2017.12.021|pmid=29335163|pmc=5821130|bibcode=2018JMagR.287..110F|issn=1090-7807}}</ref>\n\n=== Extraction of tar sands with microemulsions===\n[[Oil sands|Tar sand]]<nowiki/>s are an important source of [[bitumen]], which is extracted using water-[[surfactant]] mixtures.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Desnoyers|first=Jacques E.|last2=Quirion|first2=Fran\u00e7ois|last3=H\u00c9Tu|first3=Daniel|last4=Perron|first4=G\u00c9Rald|date=1983|title=Tar sand extractions with microemulsions: I-the dissolution of light hydrocarbons by microemulsions using 2-butoxyethanol and diethylmethylamine as cosurfactants|journal=The Canadian Journal of Chemical Engineering|volume=61|issue=5|pages=672\u2013679|doi=10.1002/cjce.5450610509|issn=0008-4034}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Lisa D.|last2=Ulrich|first2=Ania C.|date=2015-05|title=Oil sands naphthenic acids: A review of properties, measurement, and treatment|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0045653515001046|journal=Chemosphere|language=en|volume=127|pages=276\u2013290|doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2015.02.003}}</ref> Typical surfactants include alcohols, alkaline agents, and short-chain polymers. DEMA has been demonstrated to be a more effective cosurfactant in water compared to alcohol.<ref name=\":1\" /> Experimental results indicated that a monophasic region increase is observed when DEMA is used as a cosurfactant compared to [[butanol]]. The results also indicated DEMAreacts as medium-chain-length alcohol, which has both good hydrophilic-hydrophobic balance and high solubility in water and many types of oil.\n\n=== Extractive crystallization ===\nExtractive crystallization is a method of salt removal from aqueous solutions without requiring evaporative removal of water. Coordination of water molecules with polar compounds reduces the amount of water effectively available for salt solvation, resulting in crystallization, or \"crashing out\", of the salt. DEMA has been used in extractive crystallization as it has similar chemical properties to the previously used diisopropylamine(DIPA), but a [[lower critical solution temperature]] of 57\u00b0C (compared to 27 \u00b0C for DIPA; the word ''lower'' indicates that the LCST is a [[lower bound]] to a temperature interval of partial miscibility, or miscibility for certain compositions only). This precluded the necessity of refrigeration, and the energy costs associated. At low temperatures (-0.5\u00b0C), DEMAcan be used in extractive crystallization of sodium chloride; however, the percentage of sodium chloride in the organic phase is increased. The best temperature range is 5 -10 \u00b0C. In this range, the solubility of sodium chloride is relatively insensitive to temperature. DEMA can also be used in extractive crystallization of sodium sulfate at room temperature (21 - 25 \u00b0C). In this range, sodium sulfate solubility in DEMA is relatively insensitive to temperature.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ting|first=Andrew M.|last2=Lynn|first2=Scott|last3=Prausnitz|first3=John M.|date=1992-04-01|title=Liquid-liquid equilibria for aqueous systems containing N,N-diethylmethylamine and sodium chloride or sodium sulfate|journal=Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data|volume=37|issue=2|pages=252\u2013259|doi=10.1021/je00006a032|issn=0021-9568}}</ref>\n\n== DEMA in Analytical and Bio- Chemistry ==\n\n=== Interfacial bonding mechanisms between iron and DEMA ===\nMetals expected to come into contact with corrosive media are often coated with resistant polymers. However, the interfacial bonding between the polymer and metal surface is poorly understood, which led to research investigating the interaction of amides/amines (common polymer conpoments) and iron surfaces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taheri|first=P.|last2=Terryn|first2=H.|last3=Mol|first3=J.M.C.|date=2015-11-01|title=An in situ study of amine and amide molecular interaction on Fe surfaces|journal=Applied Surface Science|volume=354|pages=242\u2013249|doi=10.1016/j.apsusc.2015.08.042|bibcode=2015ApSS..354..242T|issn=0169-4332}}</ref>  Results indicate a charge-transfer mechanism between nitrogen and iron atoms. Compounds containing hydroxyl and carbonyl moieties were better substrates for iron adhesion compared to DEMA, suggesting that increased polarity is crucial for good polymer adhesion.\n\n=== DEMA effects in protic ionic liquids ===\nProtic ionic liquids (PILs) are ionic liquids formed by proton transfer from a Br\u00f8nsted acid to a Br\u00f8nsted base. in two PILs formed using DEMA as the parent amine, the addition of DEMA can have contrasting effects based on the reaction occurring on an electrode surface.  During the reduction of trifluoromethanesulfonic acid (TfOH), DEMA absorbs on the electrode surface, decreasing reaction kinetics. Conversely, formic acid oxidation is increased in the same system, due to the formation of active formate ions. The authors conclude that \"parent amines, if present in ammonium-based PILs, can inhibit or enhance electrocatalytic reactions, depending on the reaction under study, while completely different behaviour can result from changing the structure of the PIL anions.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Goodwin|first=Sean E.|last2=Muhammad|first2=Sayyar|last3=Tuan|first3=Li-Ping|last4=Walsh|first4=Darren A.|date=2018-06|title=The contrasting effects of diethylmethylamine during reduction of protons and oxidation of formic acid in diethylmethylammonium-based protic ionic liquids|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1572665717307221|journal=Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry|language=en|volume=819|pages=187\u2013192|doi=10.1016/j.jelechem.2017.10.021}}</ref>\n\n=== Enzyme kinetic studies involving DEMA ===\n[[Trimethylamine dehydrogenase]] catalyzes the oxidative demethylation of [[trimethylamine]] (TEA) and produces dimethylamine, formaldehyde, and a reduced electron-transferring flavoprotein. Substrate studies on this enzyme utilized DEMA, since the kinetics involving this unnatural substrate are slow enough to allow for detailed analysis.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rohlfs|first=R. J.|last2=Hille|first2=R.|date=1994-12-09|title=The reaction of trimethylamine dehydrogenase with diethylmethylamine|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7983019|journal=The Journal of Biological Chemistry|volume=269|issue=49|pages=30869\u201330879|issn=0021-9258|pmid=7983019}}</ref> Three distinct kinetic phases were observed, corresponding to oxidation of a flavin mononucleotide, breakdown of the flavin-substrate adduct, and product dissociation and intramolecular electron transfer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Liuxin|last2=Scrutton|first2=Nigel S.|last3=Hille|first3=Russ|date=1996-06-07|title=Reaction of the C30A Mutant of Trimethylamine Dehydrogenase with Diethylmethylamine|url=http://www.jbc.org/lookup/doi/10.1074/jbc.271.23.13401|journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry|language=en|volume=271|issue=23|pages=13401\u201313406|doi=10.1074/jbc.271.23.13401|issn=0021-9258}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Amines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Organic compound, industrial chemical}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=February 2020}}\n{{Copy edit|for=Lots of \"school essay\" commentary off-topic for article itself|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''N'',''N''-diethylmethylamine}}\n{{chembox\n| Name           = ''N'',''N''-diethylmethylamine\n| ImageFile      = Diethylmethylamine.png\n| OtherNames     = \n| IUPACName      = ''N''-ethyl-''N''-methylethanamine\n| PIN            = ''N'',''N''-Diethylmethylamine\n| SystematicName = \n| Section1       = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}}\n| CASNo=616-39-7\n| ChEMBL = 2448813\n| EINECS=210-480-5\n| PubChem=12022\n| ChemSpiderID = 11527\n| StdInChI=1S/C5H13N/c1-4-6(3)5-2/h4-5H2,1-3H3\n| StdInChIKey = GNVRJGIVDSQCOP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| SMILES = CCN(C)CC\n  }}\n| Section2       = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=5 | H=13 | N=1\n| Appearance=Volatile liquid at room temp.\n| Density= 0.72 g/mL\n| MeltingPtC=-196.0\n| BoilingPtC= 66.0\n| Solubility=310.5 g/L\n| pKa = 10.35 (for the conjugate acid) (H<sub>2</sub>O)\n  }}\n| Section3       = {{Chembox Hazards\n| MainHazards=acute toxicity\n| FlashPtF=-11\n| AutoignitionPt =\n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS02}}{{GHS05}}{{GHS06}}{{GHS07}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Danger\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|225|301|314|332}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|210|233|240|241|242|243|260|261|264|270|271|280|301+310|301+330+331|303+361+353|304+312|304+340|305+351+338|310|312|321|330|363|370+378|403+235|405|501}}\n  }}\n| Section4       = \n| Section5       = \n| Section6       = \n| Watchedfields  = \n| verifiedrevid  = \n}}\n\n'''''N'',''N''-diethylmethylamine (diethylmethylamine, DEMA)''' is a [[tertiary amine]] with the formula C<sub>5</sub>H<sub>13</sub>N. ''N'',''N''-Diethylmethylamine is a clear, colorless to pale yellow liquid at room temperature, and is used in various industrial and scientific applications including water desalination as well as analytical and organic chemistry.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zafarani-Moattar|first=Mohammed Taghi|last2=Nikjoo|first2=Dariush|date=2008-11-13|title=Liquid\u2212Liquid and Liquid\u2212Liquid\u2212Solid Equilibrium of the Poly(ethylene glycol) Dimethyl Ether 2000 + Sodium Sulfate + Water System|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/je8005858|journal=Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data|language=en|volume=53|issue=11|pages=2666\u20132670|doi=10.1021/je8005858|issn=0021-9568}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ting|first=Andrew M.|last2=Lynn|first2=Scott|last3=Prausnitz|first3=John M.|date=1 April 1992|title=Liquid-liquid equilibria for aqueous systems containing N,N-diethylmethylamine and sodium chloride or sodium sulfate|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/je00006a032|journal=Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data|language=en|volume=37|issue=2|pages=252\u2013259|doi=10.1021/je00006a032|issn=0021-9568|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Lihua|last2=Gough|first2=P. Clayton|last3=DeFelippis|first3=Michael R.|date=2009-01-15|title=Characterization of Poly(ethylene glycol) and PEGylated Products by LC/MS with Postcolumn Addition of Amines|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/ac801711u|journal=Analytical Chemistry|language=en|volume=81|issue=2|pages=567\u2013577|doi=10.1021/ac801711u|issn=0003-2700}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rohlfs|first=R. J.|last2=Hille|first2=R.|date=1994-12-09|title=The reaction of trimethylamine dehydrogenase with diethylmethylamine|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7983019|journal=The Journal of Biological Chemistry|volume=269|issue=49|pages=30869\u201330879|issn=0021-9258|pmid=7983019}}</ref>\n\nDiethylmethylamine is an acute oral and inhalation toxin although limits determining acute and chronic toxicity have not been determined, nor have the acute or chronic effects on various organ systems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://datasheets.scbt.com/sds/aghs/en/sc-236115.pdf|title=SantaCruz Biotechnology, Inc. Material Safety Data Sheet: N,N-diethylmethylamine|last=|first=|date=27 September 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Additionally, the effects of environmental exposure or accumulation are not currently known.\n\nDEMA can be converted to [[Nitrosation|nitrosated]] to its corresponding [[nitrosamine]] which may present health considerations if DEMA is used in an industrial process that involves nitrating agents at low pH or high temperatures.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nitrosation of volatile amines at the workplace [MAK Value Documentation, 1990]|date=2012|url=https://www.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/3527600418.mb0b03e0001|work=The MAK-Collection for Occupational Health and Safety|pages=24\u201337|publisher=American Cancer Society|language=en|doi=10.1002/3527600418.mb0b03e0001|isbn=978-3-527-60041-0|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/health/scientific_committees/consumer_safety/docs/sccs_o_090.pdf|title=Opinion on Nitrosamines and Secondary Amines in Cosmetic Products|last=|first=|date=27 March 2012|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The nitrosamine [[N-Nitrosodiethylamine|N-nitroso-diethylamine]] has been found in cosmetics and is a possible product of DEMA nitrosation.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, this toxic nitrosamine has only rarely been identified in cosmetic products.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are no specific storage requirements for DEMA, other than the usual precautions for storing a flammable liquid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://datasheets.scbt.com/sc-236115.pdf|title=N,N-Diethylmethylamine|last=|first=|date=|website=Santa Cruz Biotechnology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-21}}</ref>\n\n== Preparation ==\nDiethylmethylamine can be produced by [[reductive amination]] of the secondary amine [[Diethylamine|N,N-diethylamine]], in particular under [[Eschweiler\u2013Clarke reaction|Eschweiler-Clarke]] conditions, or by the catalyzed reaction between ethylamine and methanol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.organic-chemistry.org/namedreactions/eschweiler-clarke-reaction.shtm|title=Eschweiler-Clarke Reaction|website=www.organic-chemistry.org|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Pouilloux|first=Y.|title=Synthesis of dimethylethylamine from ethylamine and methanol over copper catalysts|date=1997-01-01|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167299197808981|work=Studies in Surface Science and Catalysis|volume=108|pages=139\u2013147|editor-last=Blaser|editor-first=H. U.|series=Heterogeneous Catalysis and Fine Chemicals IV|publisher=Elsevier|language=en|doi=10.1016/s0167-2991(97)80898-1|access-date=2020-04-12|last2=Doidy|first2=V.|last3=Hub|first3=S.|last4=Kervennal|first4=J.|last5=Barrault|first5=J.|editor2-last=Baiker|editor2-first=A.|editor3-last=Prins|editor3-first=R.}}</ref> A 1960 patent reports the synthesis of DEMA using [[Methyl p-toluate|methyl toluate]] and [[diethylamine]], but low yields and difficult reaction conditions make this approach infeasible for most synthetic applications.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Class|first=J.B.|title=Production of diethylemthylamine|publisher=United States Patent Office|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Properties ==\n===Molecular structure and conformation===\nThe methylene carbon-nitrogen sigma bonds in DEMA allow for multiple molecular conformations to exist, which has been studied by Bushweller et al. and, more recently, Takeuchi et al. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crocker|first=Christopher|last2=Goggin|first2=Peter L.|date=1978|title=Infrared and Raman spectroscopic studies of conformations in liquid and solid triethyl-, diethyl(methyl)- and ethyldimethyl-amines, -phosphines, and -arsines|url=http://xlink.rsc.org/?DOI=dt9780000388|journal=Journal of the Chemical Society, Dalton Transactions|language=en|issue=5|pages=388|doi=10.1039/dt9780000388|issn=0300-9246}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bushweller|first=C. Hackett|last2=Fleischman|first2=Stephen H.|last3=Grady|first3=Gilbert L.|last4=McGoff|first4=Paul|last5=Rithner|first5=Christopher D.|last6=Whalon|first6=Michael R.|last7=Brennan|first7=John G.|last8=Marcantonio|first8=Richard P.|last9=Dominigue|first9=Raymond P.|date=1982-11|title=Stereodynamics of diethylmethylamine and triethylamine|url=https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/ja00387a012|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|language=en|volume=104|issue=23|pages=6224\u20136236|doi=10.1021/ja00387a012|issn=0002-7863}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Takeuchi|first=Hiroshi|last2=Ito|first2=Masaki|last3=Egawa|first3=Toru|date=2007-09|title=Molecular structure and conformation of diethylmethylamine determined by gas electron diffraction and vibrational spectroscopy combined with theoretical calculations|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0022286006008945|journal=Journal of Molecular Structure|language=en|volume=840|issue=1-3|pages=107\u2013113|doi=10.1016/j.molstruc.2006.11.027}}</ref> These studies demonstrated the existence of four major [[Conformational isomerism|conformers]], with the ''trans-trans'' conformer possessing the greatest stability. Additional conformers were shown to exist, but represent a non-significant percentage of the conformer population at any given time and were only observed at low temperatures. Finally, pyramidal [[Pyramidal inversion|inversion]] at the nitrogen atom occurs, as shown by decoelescence of the N-CH<sub>2</sub> resonance in NMR samples that were taken at various decreasing temperatures. The data obtained in these experiments agree with data from the similar tertiary amine [[triethylamine]], leading the authors to conclude that any acyclic trialkylamine with straight-chain moieties will have similar stereodynamics compared to DEMA and triethylamine.\n\n== Usage ==\nDEMA has found use in multiple fields of study including [[nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy]] (NMR), industrial extraction techniques, and water desalination.\n\n=== Lineshape standard of nuclear magnetic resonance experiment ===\nFor a [[Carbon-13 nuclear magnetic resonance|<sup>13</sup>C NMR]] experiment, peak shape and instrument sensitivity are important considerations, and these can be optimized by adjusting the magnetic [[Shim (magnetism)|shims]] to enhance the [[magnetic field]] homogeneity and optimize peak shape. Samples used to optimize peak shape often fail at low temperatures due to peak broadening. However, DEMA has been shown to be a useful lineshape standard at temperatures down to 140K, due to its low melting point of 130K and liquid state at standard temperature and pressure. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fritzsching|first=Keith J.|last2=Itin|first2=Boris|last3=McDermott|first3=Ann E.|date=2018-02-21|title=N,N-Diethylmethylamine as lineshape standard for NMR above 130\u202fK|journal=Journal of Magnetic Resonance|volume=287|pages=110\u2013112|doi=10.1016/j.jmr.2017.12.021|pmid=29335163|pmc=5821130|bibcode=2018JMagR.287..110F|issn=1090-7807}}</ref>\n\n=== Extraction of tar sands with microemulsions===\n[[Oil sands|Tar sand]]<nowiki/>s are an important source of [[bitumen]], which is extracted using water-[[surfactant]] mixtures.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Desnoyers|first=Jacques E.|last2=Quirion|first2=Fran\u00e7ois|last3=H\u00c9Tu|first3=Daniel|last4=Perron|first4=G\u00c9Rald|date=1983|title=Tar sand extractions with microemulsions: I-the dissolution of light hydrocarbons by microemulsions using 2-butoxyethanol and diethylmethylamine as cosurfactants|journal=The Canadian Journal of Chemical Engineering|volume=61|issue=5|pages=672\u2013679|doi=10.1002/cjce.5450610509|issn=0008-4034}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brown|first=Lisa D.|last2=Ulrich|first2=Ania C.|date=2015-05|title=Oil sands naphthenic acids: A review of properties, measurement, and treatment|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0045653515001046|journal=Chemosphere|language=en|volume=127|pages=276\u2013290|doi=10.1016/j.chemosphere.2015.02.003}}</ref> Typical surfactants include alcohols, alkaline agents, and short-chain polymers. DEMA has been demonstrated to be a more effective cosurfactant in water compared to alcohol.<ref name=\":1\" /> Experimental results indicated that a monophasic region increase is observed when DEMA is used as a cosurfactant compared to [[butanol]]. The results also indicated DEMAreacts as medium-chain-length alcohol, which has both good hydrophilic-hydrophobic balance and high solubility in water and many types of oil.\n\n=== Extractive crystallization ===\nExtractive crystallization is a method of salt removal from aqueous solutions without requiring evaporative removal of water. Coordination of water molecules with polar compounds reduces the amount of water effectively available for salt solvation, resulting in crystallization, or \"crashing out\", of the salt. DEMA has been used in extractive crystallization as it has similar chemical properties to the previously used diisopropylamine(DIPA), but a [[lower critical solution temperature]] of 57\u00b0C (compared to 27 \u00b0C for DIPA; the word ''lower'' indicates that the LCST is a [[lower bound]] to a temperature interval of partial miscibility, or miscibility for certain compositions only). This precluded the necessity of refrigeration, and the energy costs associated. At low temperatures (-0.5\u00b0C), DEMAcan be used in extractive crystallization of sodium chloride; however, the percentage of sodium chloride in the organic phase is increased. The best temperature range is 5 -10 \u00b0C. In this range, the solubility of sodium chloride is relatively insensitive to temperature. DEMA can also be used in extractive crystallization of sodium sulfate at room temperature (21 - 25 \u00b0C). In this range, sodium sulfate solubility in DEMA is relatively insensitive to temperature.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ting|first=Andrew M.|last2=Lynn|first2=Scott|last3=Prausnitz|first3=John M.|date=1992-04-01|title=Liquid-liquid equilibria for aqueous systems containing N,N-diethylmethylamine and sodium chloride or sodium sulfate|journal=Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data|volume=37|issue=2|pages=252\u2013259|doi=10.1021/je00006a032|issn=0021-9568}}</ref>\n\n== DEMA in Analytical and Bio- Chemistry ==\n\n=== Interfacial bonding mechanisms between iron and DEMA ===\nMetals expected to come into contact with corrosive media are often coated with resistant polymers. However, the interfacial bonding between the polymer and metal surface is poorly understood, which led to research investigating the interaction of amides/amines (common polymer conpoments) and iron surfaces.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taheri|first=P.|last2=Terryn|first2=H.|last3=Mol|first3=J.M.C.|date=2015-11-01|title=An in situ study of amine and amide molecular interaction on Fe surfaces|journal=Applied Surface Science|volume=354|pages=242\u2013249|doi=10.1016/j.apsusc.2015.08.042|bibcode=2015ApSS..354..242T|issn=0169-4332}}</ref>  Results indicate a charge-transfer mechanism between nitrogen and iron atoms. Compounds containing hydroxyl and carbonyl moieties were better substrates for iron adhesion compared to DEMA, suggesting that increased polarity is crucial for good polymer adhesion.\n\n=== DEMA effects in protic ionic liquids ===\nProtic ionic liquids (PILs) are ionic liquids formed by proton transfer from a Br\u00f8nsted acid to a Br\u00f8nsted base. in two PILs formed using DEMA as the parent amine, the addition of DEMA can have contrasting effects based on the reaction occurring on an electrode surface.  During the reduction of trifluoromethanesulfonic acid (TfOH), DEMA absorbs on the electrode surface, decreasing reaction kinetics. Conversely, formic acid oxidation is increased in the same system, due to the formation of active formate ions. The authors conclude that \"parent amines, if present in ammonium-based PILs, can inhibit or enhance electrocatalytic reactions, depending on the reaction under study, while completely different behaviour can result from changing the structure of the PIL anions.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Goodwin|first=Sean E.|last2=Muhammad|first2=Sayyar|last3=Tuan|first3=Li-Ping|last4=Walsh|first4=Darren A.|date=2018-06|title=The contrasting effects of diethylmethylamine during reduction of protons and oxidation of formic acid in diethylmethylammonium-based protic ionic liquids|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1572665717307221|journal=Journal of Electroanalytical Chemistry|language=en|volume=819|pages=187\u2013192|doi=10.1016/j.jelechem.2017.10.021}}</ref>\n\n=== Enzyme kinetic studies involving DEMA ===\n[[Trimethylamine dehydrogenase]] catalyzes the oxidative demethylation of [[trimethylamine]] (TEA) and produces dimethylamine, formaldehyde, and a reduced electron-transferring flavoprotein. Substrate studies on this enzyme utilized DEMA, since the kinetics involving this unnatural substrate are slow enough to allow for detailed analysis.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rohlfs|first=R. J.|last2=Hille|first2=R.|date=1994-12-09|title=The reaction of trimethylamine dehydrogenase with diethylmethylamine|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7983019|journal=The Journal of Biological Chemistry|volume=269|issue=49|pages=30869\u201330879|issn=0021-9258|pmid=7983019}}</ref> Three distinct kinetic phases were observed, corresponding to oxidation of a flavin mononucleotide, breakdown of the flavin-substrate adduct, and product dissociation and intramolecular electron transfer.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Huang|first=Liuxin|last2=Scrutton|first2=Nigel S.|last3=Hille|first3=Russ|date=1996-06-07|title=Reaction of the C30A Mutant of Trimethylamine Dehydrogenase with Diethylmethylamine|url=http://www.jbc.org/lookup/doi/10.1074/jbc.271.23.13401|journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry|language=en|volume=271|issue=23|pages=13401\u201313406|doi=10.1074/jbc.271.23.13401|issn=0021-9258}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Amines]]\n", "name_user": "8BitTiger", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed proof edit tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N,N-diethylmethylamine"}
{"title_page": "Harry Albright", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n[[Image:hal.gif|right|275px|thumb|Harry Albright]]\n'''Harry James Albright''' was the Director of Communications for the [[Friends World Committee for Consultation]] (FWCC)<ref>[http://fwcc.world/about-fwcc/contact FWCC World Office]</ref> from 2008 to 2013, and editor of [[The Friend (Quaker magazine)|''The Friend'']] Magazine from 1997 to 2004.<ref>[http://www.thefriend.org/articledisplay.asp?articleid=937 the Friend \u2013 Commentary<]</ref> He is also the co-owner of a training and communications consultancy.<ref>[http://www.tcluk.com/aboutus.htm TCLuk Training]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAlbright was born in [[Geneva]], Switzerland, the son of Leland S. Albright Jr., a Canadian diplomat, and Mary Albright. He attended the [[International School of Geneva]] and [[Pickering College]] in [[Newmarket, Ontario]]. He studied journalism at [[Carleton University]] in Ottawa.\n\n==Career==\nHe was a journalist at the [[Elmira, Ontario]] ''Independent'', when it won Canada's most prestigious journalism prize, the [[Michener Award]], in 1990.<ref>[http://www.michenerawards.ca/english/winaward/1990-michener-award-winner-the-elmira-independent/ 1990 Michener Award Winner \u2013 The Elmira Independent ]</ref> The small Ontario newspaper was honoured for its blanket coverage of a prolonged legal battle over contamination of the Elmira\u2013[[St. Jacobs, Ontario|St. Jacobs]] municipal water supply. The ''Independent'' was part of the North Waterloo Publishing group, and Albright worked also on various other group titles. He was production manager for the ''Elora Sentinel'' and ''Fergus Thistle'', and news editor of the agricultural newspaper ''The Farmgate''.\n\nWith his background in agricultural journalism, Albright moved to the UK in 1993 to become the [[Public relations|press officer]] for the [[National Farmers Union (England and Wales)|National Farmers Union]] in the [[East Midlands]] region,<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/piglet-rustlers-feed-on-bacon-shortage-1319036.html The Independent \u2013 Piglet rustlers feed on bacon shortage]</ref> managing the regional response to the [[Bovine spongiform encephalopathy|BSE Crisis]] that affected the UK in the mid-1990s.\n\n==''The Friend'' and FWCC==\nIn 1997, Albright became editor of ''The Friend'', based in London, England and later communications director for FWCC, the worldwide consultative body for Quakers. He continues to serve as a consultant to various Quaker and other organizations.\n\n==Personal life==\nHarry is married to Beth Peakall and they have two children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albright, Harry}}\n[[Category:Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian Quakers]]\n[[Category:People from Geneva]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:International School of Geneva alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n[[Image:hal.gif|right|275px|thumb|Harry Albright]]\n'''Harry James Albright''' was the Director of Communications for the [[Friends World Committee for Consultation]] (FWCC)<ref>[http://fwcc.world/about-fwcc/contact FWCC World Office]</ref> from 2008 to 2013, and editor of [[The Friend (Quaker magazine)|''The Friend'']] Magazine from 1997 to 2004.<ref>[http://www.thefriend.org/articledisplay.asp?articleid=937 the Friend \u2013 Commentary<]</ref> He is also the co-owner of a training and communications consultancy.<ref>[http://www.tcluk.com/aboutus.htm TCLuk Training]</ref>\n\n==Education==\nAlbright was born in [[Geneva]], Switzerland, the son of Leland S. Albright Jr., a Canadian diplomat, and Mary Albright. He attended the [[International School of Geneva]] and [[Pickering College]] in [[Newmarket, Ontario]]. He studied journalism at [[Carleton University]] in Ottawa.\n\n==Career==\nHe was a journalist at the [[Elmira, Ontario]] ''Independent'', when it won Canada's most prestigious journalism prize, the [[Michener Award]], in 1990.<ref>[http://www.michenerawards.ca/english/winaward/1990-michener-award-winner-the-elmira-independent/ 1990 Michener Award Winner \u2013 The Elmira Independent ]</ref> The small Ontario newspaper was honoured for its blanket coverage of a prolonged legal battle over contamination of the Elmira\u2013[[St. Jacobs, Ontario|St. Jacobs]] municipal water supply. The ''Independent'' was part of the North Waterloo Publishing group, and Albright worked also on various other group titles. He was production manager for the ''Elora Sentinel'' and ''Fergus Thistle'', and news editor of the agricultural newspaper ''The Farmgate''.\n\nWith his background in agricultural journalism, Albright moved to the UK in 1993 to become the [[Public relations|press officer]] for the [[National Farmers Union (England and Wales)|National Farmers Union]] in the [[East Midlands]] region,<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/piglet-rustlers-feed-on-bacon-shortage-1319036.html The Independent \u2013 Piglet rustlers feed on bacon shortage]</ref> managing the regional response to the [[Bovine spongiform encephalopathy|BSE Crisis]] that affected the UK in the mid-1990s.\n\n==''The Friend'' and FWCC==\nIn 1997, Albright became editor of ''The Friend'', based in London, England and later communications director for FWCC, the worldwide consultative body for Quakers. He continues to serve as a consultant to various Quaker and other organizations.\n\n==Personal life==\nHarry is married to Beth Peakall and they have two children.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Albright, Harry}}\n[[Category:Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Canadian Quakers]]\n[[Category:People from Geneva]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:International School of Geneva alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Albright"}
{"title_page": "Ali (name)", "text_new": "{{About||Ali ibn Abi Talib|Ali|other uses|Ali (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox given name2\n| name = Ali<br>'''\u0639\u064e\u0644\u0650\u064a\u0651'''\n| pronunciation= {{IPA-ar|\u02c8\u0295ali\u02d0|lang}}<br>{{IPA-fa|\u0294\u00e6\u02c8li\u02d0|lang}}<br>{{IPA-tr|\u02c8ali|lang}}<br>{{IPA-ur|\u0294\u0259\u02c8li\u02d0|lang}}<br>{{IPA-fi|\u0251li|lang}}\n| gender = Male\n| meaning = Arabic: High, exalted, champion, noble<br>Finnish: Diminutive of Alexander (other languages)\n\nOriginated from: [[Arabia]]\n| language = Arabic, Azerbaijani, Persian, Turkish, Urdu, Finnish, others\n| seealso =\n| variant = Aly, Alli, Alley, Allie, Ally\n}}\n\n'''Ali''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0644\u064a}}, ''{{transl|ar|\u02bfAl\u012b}}'') is a male [[Arabic name]] derived from the Arabic root \u0295-l-w, which literally means \"high\", \"elevated\" or \"champion\". Islamic traditional use of the name goes back to the Islamic leader [[Ali|Ali ibn Abi Talib]] but the name is also present among some pre-Islamic Arabs (e.g. [[Banu Hanifa]], [[List of rulers of Saba and Himyar|some rulers of Saba and Himyar]]) and identical in form and meaning to the {{lang-he | \u05e2\u05b5\u05dc\u05b4\u05d9 }}, ''Eli'', which goes back to the [[High Priest of Israel|High Priest]] [[Eli (Bible)|Eli]] in the biblical [[Books of Samuel]].\n\nThe name ''Ali'' also arises in other traditions. Among English-speakers as short for male and female names starting with \"Al-\" such as Alice, Alison, Alistair, Alexander, or Alexandra. In [[Old Norse]], \u00c1li and \u00c5le are alternate forms of [[Onela]]. Ali is also a [[Finnish language|Finnish]] male [[given name]], derived from ''[[Alexander|Aleksanteri]]''.<ref>Kustaa Vilkuna, Marketta Huitu and Pirjo Mikkonen. ''Etunimet'', published in ''Joka kodin suuri nimikirja.'' Suuri Suomalainen Kirjakerho, 1990.</ref>\n\nAli also as a last name has become very popular on a global scale due to the spread of Islamic culture throughout the globe. This is especially so in the Caribbean where indentured laborers from South Asia were brought to replace African slave labour at the end of slavery in countries such as Guyana and Trinidad and Tobago.<ref>http://www.tntisland.com/surnames.html</ref>\n\n==Islam==\n* Al-Ali (The Sublimely Exalted)'', one of the 99 [[names of God in Islam]]\n* [[Ali]] (Ali ibn Abi Talib), cousin and son-in-law of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]], the fourth Caliph in Sunni Islam, and the first Imam in most schools of Shia Islam\n* [[Zayn al-Abidin|Ali ibn Husayn]] (''Zayn al-Abidin''), grandson of Ali ibn Abi Talib, fourth infallible Imam in Isma'ili and Twelver Shia Islam\n* [[Ali ar-Ridha|Ali ibn Musa]] (''ar-Reza''), eighth infallible Imam in Shia Islam.\n* [[Ali al-Hadi|Ali ibn Muhammad]] (''al-Hadi''), tenth infallible Imam in Shia Islam.\n\n==Given name==\n===Males===\n*[[Ali al-Sistani]], Highest-ranking Iraqi religious leader\n*[[Ali (actor)]], Telugu comedian and TV presenter\n*[[Ali (French rapper)]]\n*[[Ali (American rapper)]], aka Ali Jones, American rapper\n*[[Ali (graffiti artist)]]\n*[[Ali Aaltonen]], [[Red Guards (Finland)|Finnish Red Guard]] commander\n*[[Ali Abu Awwad]], Palestinian pacifist\n*[[Ali Akbar Navis]], Indonesian author\n*[[Ali Akdemir]], Turkish scientist\n*[[Ali al-Abdallah]], Syrian writer and human rights activist\n*[[Ali Alaaeddine]] (born 1993), Lebanese footballer\n*[[Ali Alan\u00e7]] (born 1959), Turkish football manager\n*[[Ali Alatas]], Indonesian diplomat\n*[[Ali Annabi]], Tunisian fencer\n*[[Ali Babacan]], Turkish politician\n*[[Ali Bacher]], South African cricket batsman & administrator\n*[[Ali Bozer]], Turkish politician\n*[[Ali Brownlee]] (1959\u20132016), English sportscaster\n*[[Ali \u00c7etinkaya]], Turkish Army officer\n*[[Ali Daei]] (born 1969), Iranian footballer\n*[[Ali Daher]] (born 1996), Lebanese footballer\n*[[Ali al-Dandachi]], Syrian scout leader\n*[[Ali Demi\u0107]], Bosnian basketball player\n*[[Ali Eren Demirezen]] (born 1990), Turkish amateur boxer\n*[[Ali Dizaei]] (born 1962), Anglo-Iranian police officer and criminal\n*[[Ali D\u017eabi\u010d]] (1853\u20131918), Bosnian [[mufti]]\n*[[Ali Erdemir]], Turkish scientist\n*[[Ali Fadel]], Iraqi politician\n*[[Ali Fakih]] (born 1967), Lebanese footballer\n*[[Ali Farahat]], Egyptian chess player\n*[[Ali Farokhmanesh]] (born 1988), American basketball player and coach\n*[[Ali G\u00fcne\u015f]], Turkish footballer\n*[[Nawab Ali Haider Khan|Ali Haider Khan]] (1900\u20131963), [[Nawab of Longla]]\n*[[Ali Hassan (actor) | Ali Hassan]] (born 1972), Indian television actor\n*[[Ali Hassan al-Majid]] (1941\u20132010), Iraqi politician and mass murderer\n*[[Ali Hosseinzadeh]] (born 1984), Iranian Composer and Record Producer\n*[[Ali \u0130smet \u00d6zt\u00fcrk]] (born 1964), Turkish aerobatics pilot\n*[[Ali Jarbawi]], Palestinian politician\n*[[Ali Kaya]] (born Stanley Kiprotich Mukche in 1994), Kenyan-Turkish long-distance runner\n*[[Ali Kaya (serial killer)]] (born 1979), Turkish serial killer\n*[[Ali Kemal Bey]], Turkish journalist, newspaper editor and poet\n*[[Ali Khademhosseini]] (born 1975), Iranian-Canadian bioengineer\n*[[Ali Kire\u015f]], Turkish footballer\n*[[Ali Kordan]] (1958\u20132009), Iranian politician\n*[[Ali ibn Abbas al-Majusi]], 11th century physician\n*[[Ali Moulana]], Sri Lankan politician, chairman of [[Eravur Urban Council]]\n*[[Ali Maksum]], Indonesian Islamic leader\n*[[Ali Marpet]] (born 1993), American football player in the NFL\n*[[Ali Marwi]], Kuwaiti footballer\n*[[Ali Musse]] (born 1996), Somali footballer\n*[[Ali Noorzad]], Afghan basketball player\n*[[Ali Nuhi\u0107]], German-born Bosnian footballer\n*[[Ali \u00d6lmez]], Turkish footballer\n*[[Ali Omari]], Afghan footballer\n*[[Ali \u00d6zgent\u00fcrk]], Turkish film director\n*[[Ali \u00d6zt\u00fcrk (footballer born 1986)]], Turkish footballer\n*[[Ali \u00d6zt\u00fcrk (footballer born 1987)]], Turkish footballer\n*[[Ali Rehman Khan]], Pakistani Actor\n*[