Chief Designer: Hiroshi Hasegawa\n  | Design Director: Shiro Nakamura\n  }}\n| class = {{unbulleted list\n  | [[Sports car]] ([[S-segment|S]])<!-- per [[WP:CARCLASS]], this should not be changed to \"supercar\" or \"hypercar\" -->\n  | [[Grand tourer]] ([[S-segment|S]])\n  }}\n| body_style = 2-door [[2+2 (car body style)|2+2]] seater [[coup\u00e9]]\n| platform = [[Nissan PM platform|Nissan Premium Midship]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, all-wheel drive]]\n| engine = 3.8&nbsp;L [[twin-turbocharged]] [[Nissan VR engine#VR38DETT|''VR38DETT'' V6]]\n| powerout = {{ubl | {{convert|357|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} (2007\u20132011) | {{convert|530|\u2013|550|PS|kW|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} (2011\u20132017) | {{convert|570|PS|kW|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} (2017\u2013present) | {{convert|609|PS|kW|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} (NISMO & Track Edition) | {{convert|720|PS|kW|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} (GT-R50)}}\n| transmission = 6-speed [[Dual-clutch transmission|dual clutch]] transmission\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2780|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{unbulleted list\n  | 2009\u20132010: {{convert|183.3|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n  | 2011 \u2013 present: {{convert|183.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n  }}\n| width = {{unbulleted list\n  | 2009\u20132010 & 2013\u2013: {{convert|74.6|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n  | 2011\u201312: {{convert|74.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n  }}\n| height = {{unbulleted list\n  | 2009\u20132010 & 2013\u2013: {{convert|53.9|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n  | 2011\u20132012: {{convert|54.0|in|mm|0|abbr=on}}\n  }}\n| weight = {{convert|1740|kg|lb||abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[Nissan Skyline GT-R]] (R34)\n}}\n\nThe '''Nissan GT-R''' is a high-performance [[sports car]] and [[grand tourer]] produced by [[Nissan]], which was unveiled in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caranddriver.com/previews/14221/first-look-2009-nissan-gt-r.html |title=First Drive Review - 2009 Nissan GT-R |author=Tony Swan |website=www.caranddriver.com |date=December 2007 |access-date=October 21, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edmunds.com/il/nissan/skyline/index.html |title=2009 Nissan Skyline GT-R |publisher=Inside Line |website=www.edmunds.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026011926/http://www.edmunds.com/il/nissan/skyline/index.html |archive-date=October 26, 2007 |access-date=October 21, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/coupes/112_0712_2008_nissan_gt_r/ |title=First Look: 2008 Nissan GT-R |publisher=MotorTrend |author=Edward Loh |website=www.motortrend.com |date=October 25, 2007 |access-date=October 21, 2017 }}</ref> It is the successor to the [[Nissan Skyline GT-R|Skyline GT-R]], although no longer part of the [[Nissan Skyline|Skyline range]] itself, that name now being used for Nissan's luxury-sport market.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Nissan Skyline GT-R}}\n\nBetween 1969 and 1974, and again between 1989 and 2002, [[Nissan]] produced a high performance version of its Skyline coupe called the Nissan Skyline GT-R. This car proved to be iconic for Nissan<ref name=\"evo.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.evo.co.uk/features/features/223512/nissan_skyline_gtr.html |title=Nissan Skyline GT-R |author=Ian Eveleigh |website=www.evo.co.uk |date=June 11, 2008 |access-date=October 9, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zimbio.com/Nissan+Skyline+GT-R|title=Nissan Skyline GT-R|publisher=Zimbio|page=1|accessdate=October 9, 2008}}</ref> and achieved much fame and success on both road and track.\n[[File:Nissan_GT-R_Taillights_-_CarSpotter.jpg|alt=|220x220px|[[Nissan Skyline GT-R]]'s signature four round tail lights succeeded on the Nissan GT-R.|left|thumb]]\n\nThe GT-R is an entirely new model sharing little with the Skyline GT-R save its signature four round tail lights. Like some later generations of the Skyline GT-R, the GT-R has [[all-wheel drive]] with a twin-turbocharged [[V6|6-cylinder]] engine. But the four-wheel-steering [[HICAS]] system has been removed and the former [[straight-6]] [[RB26DETT]] engine has been replaced with a new [[Nissan VR engine|VR38DETT V6 engine]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Under the hood of the Nissan GT-R |publisher=Autoblog |date=September 11, 2007 |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2007/09/11/under-the-hood-of-the-nissan-gt-r/ |accessdate=September 11, 2007}}</ref> Because of the GT-R's heritage, the chassis code for the all-new version has been called '''CBA-R35''',<ref>{{cite press release |title=Nissan GT-R Press Information \u2013 Specifications |publisher=Nissan |url=http://press.nissan-global.com/PRESSKIT/NISSANGTR/0710/ENGLISH/LINEUP_SPECIFICATIONS/index2.html |accessdate=November 1, 2007}}</ref> or '''R35''' for short (where CBA stands for the emissions standard prefix), carrying on the naming trend from previous Skyline GT-R generations.\n\nThe GT-R has also retained its Skyline predecessor's nickname, [[Godzilla]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.drive.com.au/drive/motor-news/nissan-gtr-godzilla-returns-to-australia-20080229-143cp.html|title=Nissan GT-R: 'Godzilla' returns...|last=Blackburn|first=Richard|date=February 29, 2008|publisher=drive.com.au|page=1|accessdate=August 26, 2008}}</ref> originally given to it by the Australian motoring publication Wheels in its July 1989 edition.\n\n===Concepts===\n[[File:NISSAN GT-R CONCEPT at TMS2001 003.jpg|thumb|left|2001 GT-R Concept at the [[Tokyo Motor Show#2001|2001 Tokyo Motor Show]]|alt=]]\n[[File:Nissan GT-R PROTO.jpg|thumb|GT-R Proto Concept at the [[Tokyo Motor Show#2005|2005 Tokyo Motor Show]]|alt=]]Nissan showed two GT-R concept cars at motor shows before it unveiled the production model: one at the [[Tokyo Motor Show#2001|Tokyo Motor Show]] in 2001, to preview a 21st-century GT-R;<ref>{{cite web |title=2001 Nissan GT-R Concept |publisher=JB car pages |url=http://www.jbskyline.net/V35/GTRConcept/ |accessdate=June 22, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703155541/http://www.jbskyline.net/V35/GTRConcept/ |archivedate=July 3, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and a redesigned one, dubbed GT-R Proto, at the [[Tokyo Motor Show#2005|2005 Tokyo Motor Show]]. Officials said the production GT-R would be 80 to 90% based on the second concept.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=107616 |title=TOKYO NEWS: Nissan Reveals Juicy Tidbits About 2007 GT-R Sports car |date=October 18, 2005 |publisher=edmunds.com |page=1 |accessdate=August 26, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017234100/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=107616 |archivedate=October 17, 2007}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Production==\n===Production model===\nThe production version of the GT-R debuted at the 2007 [[Tokyo Motor Show]] as the 2009 model year, with a lap time of 7:38 minutes at the [[N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife lap times|N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife]] beating the all time sports classic [[Porsche 911 Turbo]] as Nissan stated before launching the car.<ref>{{Citation|title=Nissan GTR DOCUMENTARY|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4DZF-BxK3aU|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> The GT-R launched in the Japanese market on December 6, 2007. The U.S. official launch was seven months later on July 7, 2008. Universal Nissan in Los Angeles provided a customer with the delivery of a new GT-R, fresh from the production line at 12:01&nbsp;am, on July 7, 2008. The Canadian launch was also in July 2008. Europe became the third consumer market, where it launched in March 2009. The large disparity in initial marketing between these regional releases is due to Nissan having to build GT-R performance centers where the car is serviced.\n\nThe engines are hand built by only four specially trained mechanics called \"Takumi Craftsmens\" on a special line at Nissan's Yokohama plant and their names are badged on every GT-R engine. The cars are built at their Tochigi plant on a shared production line.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dalle Carbonare |first1=Dino |title=Car Builder>> How The Nissan Gt-r Is Built |url=http://www.speedhunters.com/2009/07/car_builder_gt_gt_how_the_nissan_gt_r_is_built/ |website=Speedhunters |access-date=April 17, 2019 |date=July 28, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180812042324/http://www.speedhunters.com/2009/07/car_builder_gt_gt_how_the_nissan_gt_r_is_built/ |archive-date=August 12, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Perry |first1=Joanne |title=Nissan Tochigi's human touch |url=https://automotivemanufacturingsolutions.com/focus/the-human-touch |website=Automotive Manufacturing Solutions |date=August 14, 2017 |access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Takumi: The Master Craftsmen behind Each Nissan GT-R |url=https://reports.nissan-global.com/EN/?p=10948 |publisher=Nissan |access-date=April 17, 2019 |date=July 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>''[[National Geographic]]'' [[Ultimate Factories]], Season 6 (2013)</ref>\n\n====Design====\n[[File:Nissan GTR - Flickr - Alexandre Pr\u00e9vot (12).jpg|thumb|A rear view of the GT-R, showing the signature taillights first offered in 1972 on the [[Nissan Skyline#C110|Skyline C110]]|alt=]]\n\nNissan chief creative officer, Shir\u014d Nakamura, has likened the new GT-R to the [[Real Robot|giant robots]] of the ''[[Gundam]]'' series.<ref name=\"businessweek2007\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/innovate/content/nov2007/id20071119_902449.htm |title=Nissan Redesigns a Japanese Icon |work=BusinessWeek |author=Matt Vella |date=November 26, 2007<!--, 3:57&nbsp;pm EST -->|accessdate=October 27, 2008}}</ref> Nakamura stated: \"The GT-R is unique because it is not simply a copy of a European-designed Sports car; it had to really reflect [[Japanese culture]].\"\n\nNissan's American designers sculpted the rear three quarters of the vehicle, while their European designers sculpted the roofline.<ref name=\"businessweek2007\"/>\n\n[[Polyphony Digital]], creators of the [[Gran Turismo (series)|''Gran Turismo'']] series of motor racing video games, were themselves involved in the development of the GT-R, having been contracted to design the GT-R's multifunction display.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/Features/articleId=123066 |title=Edmunds Inside Line: A Day in Germany With the GT-R Engineers |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018104650/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/Features/articleId=123066 |archivedate=October 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2009 Nissan GT-R Black Edition - Flickr - The Car Spy (18).jpg|thumb|left|The customizable multifunction display integrated into the dash of the GT-R that had its roots in the R34 Skyline.]]\n\n[[File:The interior of Nissan GT-R Premium Edition 2017 year model at Nissan Global Headquarters Gallery.jpg|thumb|left|Interior]]\n\n=====Nissan PM platform=====\n{{Asof|2014}} the GT-R was the only model built on Nissan's Premium Midship (PM) platform,<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://nissannews.com/en-CA/nissan/canada/presskits/ca-2014-nissan-gt-r-press-kit |title=2014 Nissan GT-R Press Kit |publisher=Nissan |location=Canada |quote=The Nissan GT-R's unique Premium Midship platform, created expressly for use with the GT-R... |access-date=October 21, 2017 }}</ref> an evolution of the [[Nissan FM platform|Front Midship (FM)]] architecture introduced on the [[Nissan Skyline#V35/CPV35|2001 (V35) Skyline]]. It is a hybrid [[unibody]] assembled on ultra-low-tolerance jigs similar to those used in race car construction. Alcoa aluminium is used for the hood, trunk lid and outer door skins, with die-cast aluminium front shock towers and inner door structures. Outer body panels are stamped using multiple-strike coining process for added rigidity and precision. The chassis is stiffened with a carbon-composite front crossmember/radiator support.\n\n=====Exterior=====\nNissan developed a 6-stage paint process with double clear coat and chip-resistant paint for use in critical areas of the GT-R chassis. An optional liquid-effect finish employs a hand-polished 8-stage process with product-specific Super Silver metallic paint and three layers of [[Automotive paint#Clearcoat|clearcoat]].\n\n=====Optional features=====\nThe Premium trim for the GT-R has a body-coloured rear spoiler whereas the Black Edition has a dry carbon-fibre rear spoiler. Both the Premium and Black Edition models are fitted with (LED) headlights, automatic on/off headlights, LED daytime running lights, LED taillights and brake lights, dual heated body-colour power wing mirrors, power folding wing mirrors, flush-mounted aluminium door handles, four 5-inch exhaust outlets with polished tips and UV-reducing solar glass.<ref name=\"nissanusa1\">[http://www.nissanusa.com/gt-r/specifications.html 2013 Nissan GT-R | Specifications]. Nissan USA.</ref>\n\n====Specifications====\n[[File:Nissan GT-R engine.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Nissan VR engine|VR38DETT]] engine]]\n\nThe Nissan GT-R is powered by the [[Nissan VR engine|VR38DETT]] V6 engine, a {{convert|3799|cc|L cuin|1|abbr=on}} [[DOHC]] V6 with [[plasma transferred wire arc]] sprayed [[cylinder bore]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nissanusa.com/sportscars/gt-r/versions-specs |title=2019 Nissan GT-R Specs |publisher=Nissan |location=US |access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> Two parallel [[IHI Corporation|Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries]] (IHI) turbochargers provide [[forced induction]].<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2007/_STORY/071024-01-e.html |title=Nissan Press Release \u2013 Nissan Announces New Nissan GT-R |publisher=Nissan |date=October 24, 2007 |accessdate=October 24, 2007}}</ref> Models manufactured between 2007 and 2010 are rated at a manufacturer-claimed engine output of {{convert|357|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,400&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|434|lbft|N.m|abbr=on}} at 3200\u20135,200&nbsp;rpm.<ref>{{cite web |title=NISSAN GT-R : LA SUPERCAR EN TOUTE CIRCONSTANCE |url=https://france.nissannews.com/fr-FR/releases/release-1575-nissan-gt-r-la-supercar-en-toute-circonstance |website=Site Presse de Nissan |accessdate=28 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gtrnissan.com/ |title=Nissan GT-R Specification |work=Nissan |accessdate=September 25, 2008}}</ref> The engine also meets [[California Air Resources Board]] [[Ultra Low Emission Vehicle]] (ULEV) standards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jbcarpages.com/nissan/gtr/2009/features/ |title=Nissan GT-R Features|work=JB car pages |accessdate=June 22, 2008}}</ref>\nThe standard GT-R and the NISMO GT-R has a {{Cd|long=yes|link=car|0.26}}.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.caranddriver.com/news/a15102356/2017-nissan-gt-r-gets-more-power-news |title=2017 Nissan GT-R Gets Exterior Revisions, More Cowbell |last=Johnson |first=Davey G. |work=Car and Driver |date=March 23, 2016 |access-date=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA [[curb weight]] of {{convert|1730|or|1736|kg|lb|abbr=on}} with side curtain [[airbags]] is achieved using a jig welded steel chassis with aluminium used for the hood, trunk, and doors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nissan-global.com/EN/GTR/|title=NISSAN &#124; Nissan GT-R &#124; GT-R in your Region|website=www.nissan-global.com}}</ref> A rear mounted six-speed [[BorgWarner]] designed [[dual clutch transmission|dual clutch]] [[semi-automatic transmission]] built by Aichi Machine Industry shifting gears in just 0.15 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aichikikai.co.jp/en/corporate/history/index.html |title=Aichi Kikai manufacturing history |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018065637/http://www.aichikikai.co.jp/en/corporate/history/index.html |archivedate=October 18, 2010 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> is used in conjunction with the [[ATTESA E-TS]] system to provide power to all four wheels and along with Nissan's [[stability control|Vehicle Dynamics Control]] (VDC-R) to aid in stability. Three shift modes can also be selected for various conditions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=126032 |title=Fast Times: Nissan GT-R Sets New Nurburgring Record |work=[[Edmunds.com|Edmunds]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502172709/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=126032 |archivedate=May 2, 2008}}</ref>\nBeginning in 2010, engine power and torque were upgraded to {{convert|390|kW|PS hp|0||abbr=on}} at 6,400&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|612|Nm|abbr=on}} at 3,200\u20136,000&nbsp;rpm respectively. Models produced in 2012 again featured improved engine output ({{convert|406.5|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,400&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|628|Nm|abbr=on}} at 3,200\u20135,800&nbsp;rpm), and to the 2017 model year Nissan again increased the engine output ({{convert|419|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,400&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|633|Nm|abbr=on|}} at 3,200\u20135,800&nbsp;rpm).\n\n====2011 facelift====\n[[File:2013 Nissan GT-R -- 06-23-2012 1.JPG|thumb|left|A 2013 Nissan GT-R Premium with the updated design]]\n\nThe revised GT-R features an engine with revised mapping, changes to valve timing, larger inlets and a revised exhaust system which boosts rated power to {{convert|406|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.nissannews.com/newsrelease.do?id=2093&mid= |title=Nissan and Infiniti \u2013 2012 Nissan GT-R Features More Horsepower, New \"Black Edition,\" Revised Fascias and Carbon Fiber Interior Trim |publisher=Nissan |location=US |date=November 17, 2010 |accessdate=November 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231230901/http://nissannews.com/newsrelease.do?id=2093&mid= |archivedate=December 31, 2010}}</ref> and {{convert|612|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque from 3,200 to 6,000 rpm. Changes also include a new more rigid front strut bar made from carbon composite, larger front brake rotors, new lighter and stiffer wheels, and revised Dunlop tires. Cosmetic changes include a new front bumper with integrated [[LED]]s. The front bumper improves cooling to the radiator and front brakes while reducing drag. A new rear diffuser improves downforce and also includes additional rear cooling ducts. The interior was revised to improve the quality. The new model is offered with a new HDD CARWINGS navigation system with enhanced entertainment features and USB port with iPod connectivity. The revised GT-R went on sale in Japan from mid November 2010 and February 2011 in Europe, North America and other regions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://motoring.asiaone.com/Motoring/News/Story/A1Story20101019-243030.html |title=2011 Nissan GT-R}}</ref>\n\n====2017 facelift====\n[[File:Edmonton Motor Show 2017 (33392947594).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|220x220px|2017 Nissan GT-R with new updates.]]\nThe updated Nissan GT-R has the same twin-turbocharged {{convert|3799|cc|L cuin|1|abbr=on}} V6 [[VR38DETT]] engine. but increased the engine output to ({{convert|419|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,400&nbsp;rpm and {{convert|633|Nm||abbr=on}} at 3,200\u20135,800&nbsp;rpm). The transmission system is also refined to shift the gears quicker than before.\n\nOther updates include a new front and rear end, bumpers design have been added to improve air cooling system and aerodynamics, new leather has been added to whole interior with a new steering wheel, new infotainment systems and redesigned centre console, new 20-inch aluminium forged wheels, new suspension system, new titanium exhaust system, and new braking systems were added to newly updated GT-R.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/a15100625/2017-nissan-gt-r-first-drive-review|title=2017 Nissan GT-R|last=Sherman|first=Don|date=2016-06-03|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Models ==\n===SpecV===\n{{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal vertical | width = 220\n| image1 = NISSAN GT-R SpecV.jpg\n| image2 = NISSAN GT-R SpecV rear.jpg\n| caption2 = GT-R SpecV\n}}\n\nNissan introduced the GT-R SpecV on January 7, 2009 at the 2009 [[Tokyo Auto Salon]]. This version uses [[carbon fibre]] trim inside and out, and has no rear seats.<ref name=\"ABspecv\">{{cite web|author=Damon Lavrinc RSS feed |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/01/07/nissan-gt-r-specv-unveiled/ |title=Nissan GT-R SpecV unveiled! |publisher=Autoblog.com |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref> In addition, a new colour was introduced limited to the SpecV, LAC Black Opal,<ref name=en-r35-colours>{{cite web |url=http://gtr-registry.com/en-r35-colours.php |title=Nissan Skyline R35 GT-R Colour Breakdown|website=GTR-Registry.com |access-date=April 29, 2017}}</ref> The car came with Bridgestone Potenza RE070R tyres.<ref name=\"Autocar-2009-03-30\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-review/nissan/gt-r/first-drives/nissan-gt-r-spec-v |title=Nissan GT-R Spec V first drive |work=Autocar |location=UK |date=March 30, 2009 |access-date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe GT-R SpecV is powered by the standard twin-turbocharged {{convert|3799|cc|L cuin|1|abbr=on}} V6. A new high gear boost controller that allows a temporary increase in boost pressure to the [[IHI Corporation|IHI]] twin turbochargers, now larger than those on the standard GT-R, delivering {{cvt|15|lbft|order=flip|0}} more torque than the standard GT-R in mid to high-range revs.<ref name=\"Autocar-2009-03-30\" /> Other mechanical changes include a titanium exhaust, Recaro bucket seats,<ref name=\"Autocar-2009-03-30\" /> reworked suspension, carbon ceramic brakes, and {{convert|20|in|mm|adj=on}} NISMO wheels. Overall weight is decreased by {{convert|132|lb|kg|abbr=on|order=flip}} over the standard GT-R.<ref name=\"JPspecvVideo\">{{cite web|url=http://jalopnik.com/5126884/nissan-gt+r-specv-super+godzilla-caught-on-tape|title=Nissan GT-R SpecV: Super-Godzilla Caught On Tape |publisher=Jalopnik.com |date=January 9, 2009 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nSales began in Japan on February 2, 2009 at seven preselected dealers staffed specially trained mechanics knowledgeable about racing circuit driving. The price was {{yen|15,750,000}} (about {{US$|160,000}}). The SpecV was also sold in Europe and the Middle East. A total of 110<ref name=en-r35-specv>{{cite web |url=http://gtr-registry.com/en-r35-specv.php |title=Nissan Skyline R35 GT-R SpecV|website=GTR-Registry.com |access-date=April 29, 2017}}</ref> SpecV were built, 77 for Japan, 24 for Europe, 1 for United Kingdom, 7 for Middle East and 1 additional car.\n\n''[[Auto Express]]'' tested the SpecV and posted a {{cvt|0\u201397|km/h}} time of 3.20&nbsp;seconds, {{convert|1/4|mile|m|abbr=out}} time of 11.5 seconds, pulled 1.12&nbsp;g on the skidpad and 120.2&nbsp;km/h in the slalom. An earlier tested [[Chevrolet Corvette C6 ZR1]] resulted in an identical slalom speed but a lower 1.06&nbsp;g on the skidpad.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jonathon Ramsey RSS feed |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/04/28/video-autoexpress-tests-the-2010-nissan-gt-r-specv/ |title=Video: AutoExpress tests the 2010 Nissan GT-R SpecV |publisher=Autoblog.com |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Black Edition===\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150\">\nNISSAN_GT-R_R35_2011.JPG|\nNISSAN_GT-R_R35_2011_R.JPG\n</gallery>\n\nThe Black Edition comes with exclusive 20-inch RAYS wheels and a carbon fibre rear spoiler. [[Recaro]] racing seats were commissioned specifically by Nissan for the Black Edition. The interior is finished in red and black leather, but a beige colour known as 'Pale Ivory' is also available. No mechanical changes are made from the standard GT-R.\n\n===Track Edition===\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150\">\nOSAKA_AUTO_MESSE_2015_(102)_-_Nissan_GT-R_Track_Edition_engineered_by_NISMO_(DBA-R35).JPG|\nOSAKA_AUTO_MESSE_2015_(101)_-_Nissan_GT-R_Track_Edition_engineered_by_NISMO_(DBA-R35).JPG\n</gallery>\n\nIn 2013, for the 2014 model year, Nissan introduced a limited production Track Edition GT-R which deletes the rear seats (saving {{cvt|22|lb|kg|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} over the Black Edition) and adds stiffer suspension, carbon fibre air inlets, improved brake cooling, a unique front spoiler, and new black and gray leather [[Recaro]] front seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automoblog.net/2013/05/02/limited-run-2014-nissan-gt-r-track-edition/|title=Fast Favorite: Limited Run 2014 Nissan GT-R,09iu Track Edition|date=May 2, 2013|publisher=Automoblog.net|accessdate=May 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''[[Motor Trend]]'' tested the 2014 model year Track Edition GT-R, achieving {{cvt|0-60|mph|km/h|0|order=flip}} in 2.7 seconds, {{convert|1/4|mile|m|abbr=out}} in 10.8 seconds at {{cvt|125.1|mph|km/h|1|order=flip}}.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.motortrend.ca/en/news/2013-nissan-gt-r-track-pack-japanese-spec/ |title=First Drive: 2013 Nissan GT-R Track Pack Japanese Spec |last=Lyon |first=Peter |date=November 23, 2011 |work=Motor Trend |url-status=live |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The German car magazine [[Sport auto (Germany)|sport auto]] tested the top speed of the Track Edition GT-R, and achieved a top speed of {{cvt|333|km/h|mph|0}}.<ref>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TrWGApUt0wQ |last=cc8186 |title=Nissan GT-R Track Pack 0-333 km/h 2012 R35 Top Speed Launch Control sport auto |date=2012-09-07 |access-date=2019-06-27 |via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nAt the April 2019 [[New York Auto Show]], Nissan introduced the 2020 model year GT-R Track Edition. The car gets it's drivetrain from the NISMO GT-R's twin-turbocharged {{cvt|3799|cc|L cuin|1|order=flip}} V6 [[Nissan VR engine|VR38DETT]] engine with {{cvt|448|kW|PS hp|0|order=flip}} at 6,800 rpm and {{convert|652|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3,200-5,800 rpm and gets a 20% of increase in acceleration reaction time compared to the previous model year GT-R Track Edition. Other updates includes a NISMO tuned independent suspension system, new dry carbon fibre roof reducing weight, NISMO front fenders, new [[Rays Engineering|RAYS]] 20-inch NISMO forged aluminium alloy wheels with [[Dunlop Tyres|Dunlop]] 255/40RF-20 run-flat SP Sport Maxx GT 600 DSST NISMO-spec tires and dry carbon-fiber rear spoiler. The Track Edition includes new re-designed red and black colour treatment for interior with high-grip [[Recaro]] seats.<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://usa.nissannews.com/en-US/releases/2020-nissan-gt-r-press-kit |title=2020 Nissan GT-R Press Kit |publisher=Nissan |location=US |date=2019-05-14 |access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n===GT-R NISMO===\n[[File:The frontview of Nissan GT-R NISMO Mid-year 2020.jpg|thumb|right|2020 model year GT-R NISMO.]]\n[[Nissan]] introduced the GT-R NISMO for 2015 as the world's fastest volume production vehicle around [[N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife]] with a lap time of 7:08.679 minutes in [[Tokyo Motor Show|2014 Tokyo Motor Show]].\n\nIn the new model, power increases to {{convert|441|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,800 rpm and {{convert|652|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque at 3,200-5,800 rpm. The {{convert|0-60|mph|km/h|abbr=on|0|order=flip}} time changed to 2.5 seconds.<ref name=\"evo-7305\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.evo.co.uk/nissan/gtr/7305/nissan-gt-r-nismo-review-price-specs-and-0-60-time |title=Nissan GT-R Nismo review, price, specs and 0-60 time |first=Nick |last=Trott |work=Evo |location=UK |date=August 15, 2015 |access-date=April 6, 2019}}</ref> The [[gear-ratio]]s did not change in the [[dual-clutch transmission]]. The [[fuel tank]] capacity is {{convert|74|L|USgal impgal|1|abbr=on|order=flip}}. Additional front and rear brake cooling ducts are added, and a full NISMO tuned suspension is installed, including a hollow {{cvt|17.3|mm|abbr=on}} rear [[stabilizer bar]] from the NISMO performance division.\n\nSpecial edition forged alloys by RAYS in 20-inch size are included. The standard GT-R's aluminium [[trunk lid]] is swapped out for a full [[Carbon fiber reinforced polymer#Automotive engineering|carbon fibre]] panel and additional [[Spot welding|spot welds]] and adhesive help strengthen the chassis. A front splitter with carbon fibre [[air duct]]s up front add to the special NISMO full aerodynamic package, while a large racing style carbon wing completes the rear.\n\nInside, the NISMO edition has special seats with black and red colour treatment made with synthetic [[suede]]. The instrument binnacle and steering wheel are also covered in synthetic suede. The [[Bose Corporation|Bose]] [[stereo system]] does not have [[active noise control]]. The gauges have some red colour treatment as well. NISMO-specific options are low-gloss matte gray paint and a full titanium exhaust with additional [[heatsinks]]. These changes, in aggregate, reduce weight by {{cvt|38|lb|abbr=on|order=flip}}, which is the reason that the NISMO GT-R accelerates even faster than before.\n\nAt the 2019 [[New York Auto Show]], Nissan unveiled the 2020 GT-R NISMO and the 50th anniversary GT-R for the GT-R's 50th anniversary. Updates to the NISMO GT-R include a new \"R mode\" gear shifting setting to shift gears more quickly, new turbochargers from the GT3 race car to improve the acceleration, RAYS 20-inch wheels, GT3-inspired fender vents, lightweight carbon ceramic brakes, new re-tuned suspension and the roof, hood and fenders are made with carbon fibre to reduce the weight. Nissan says new NISMO GT-R is faster and more track focused than previous models, and the weight has been reduced by 20&nbsp;kg compared to the 2017 model year NISMO GT-R.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.motor1.com/news/345032/nissan-gt-r-anniversary-bayside-blue/ |title=2020 Nissan GT-R 50th Anniversary Edition Brings Back Bayside Blue |first=Christopher |last=Smith |work=Motor1 |location=US |date=April 18, 2019 |access-date=April 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nissanusa.com/vehicles/future-concept/2020-gt-r.html |title=2020 Nissan GT-R Sports Car |publisher=Nissan |location=US |access-date=April 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 2019, Nissan's Hiroshi Tamura visited ''[[Motor Trend]]'' for an interview to talk about the 2020 Nissan GT-R NISMO. He said the acceleration from {{cvt|0|to|50|mph|km/h|order=flip|0}} is quicker by {{cvt|8|feet|m|order=flip|1}} because of improvement on acceleration. He also said that the lap time of the [[Nurburgring Nordschleife]] will be quicker by 5 seconds compared to the 2017 model year GT-R NISMO because of a 5% improvement in cornering force and better braking performance.<ref name=\"MotorTrend-2020\">{{cite news |url=https://www.motortrend.com/cars/nissan/gt-r/2020/2020-nissan-gt-r-nismo-first-drive-review/amp/ |title=2020 Nissan GT-R Nismo First Drive: The Art of Continuous Improvement |last=MacKenzie |first=Angus |website=Motor Trend |location=US |date=July 8, 2019 |access-date=August 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Nissan]] claimed the price for the 2020 model year GT-R NISMO of US$ 210,740.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nissanusa.com/vehicles/sports-cars/gt-r.html|title=2020 Nissan GT-R Sports Car |publisher=Nissan |location=US |access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref> and the car can accelerate {{cvt|0-60|mph|km/h|0|order=flip}} in 2.48 seconds, and achieve a top speed of {{cvt|205|mph|km/h|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"TopSpeed-ar187537\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topspeed.com/cars/nissan/2020-nissan-gt-r-nismodriven-ar187537.html|title=2020 Nissan GT-R Nismo - Driven @ Top Speed|date=2020-01-21|website=Top Speed|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref name=\"Supercars-Nismo\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.supercars.net/blog/2020-nissan-gt-r-nismo-guide-history-specifications-performance/|title=2020 Nissan GT-R Nismo: History, Specifications, & Performance|date=2019-07-16|website=Supercars.net|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n===GT-R NISMO N-Attack===\nA special edition of the GT-R NISMO which is outfitted after the purchase of the NISMO model. This package includes the parts which the original GT-R NISMO has when racing for the fastest lap time on the N\u00fcrburgring track. For Japan, installation is handled by NISMO Omori factory. For North America, the conversion is handled by STILLEN.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stillen.com/|title=Aftermarket & Performance Parts - Auto Parts & Accessories - STILLEN|website=www.stillen.com}}</ref>{{multiple image\n| align = center\n| direction = horizontal vertical\n| width = 220\n| total_width =\n| image1 = Nissan GT-R NISMO N Attack Package (DBA-R35) front.JPG\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 =\n| image2 = Nissan GT-R NISMO N Attack Package (DBA-R35) rear.JPG\n| caption2 = GT-R NISMO N-Attack\n}}\n===GT-R50===\n[[File:GIMS 2019, Le Grand-Saconnex (GIMS0728).jpg|thumb|Nissan GT-R50 concept on display]]\nTo celebrate the GT-R's 50th anniversary, Nissan has announced that, in 2019, they will introduce a limited-production GT-R called the GT-R50. Only fifty of these cars will be produced with a price tag of US$ 1.1 million and the car became the most expensive vehicle produced by Nissan. The GT-R50 shares its powertrain with the GT-R NISMO but is rated at {{cvt|530|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} and {{cvt|780|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.carsales.com.au/editorial/details/nissan-gt-r50-by-italdesign-to-cost-1-4m-plus-113545/ |title=Nissan GT-R50 by Italdesign to cost $1.4m-plus |work=carsales |location=Australia |date=July 9, 2018 |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/12/10/success/nissan-gt-r50/index.html |title=Nissan to sell limited edition GT-R50 sports car for $1.1 million |first=Peter |last=Valdes-Dapena |work=CNN |location=US |date=December 16, 2018 |access-date=December 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUpgrades to the engine include large diameter turbochargers shared with the GT3 specification GT-R, a heavy duty crankshaft, pistons and connecting rods, a modified intake system, a new exhaust system, a recalibrated gearbox and a reinforced differential. The rear suspension system uses Bilstein continuously variable dampers and the car uses carbon ceramic brakes. The GT-R50 comes standard in 21-inch carbon fibre wheels with Michelin Pilot Super Sport tyres.\n\nThe design of the body work is a result of a collaboration between [[Italdesign Giugiaro|Italdesign]] and Nissan, with the former celebrating its 50th anniversary in 2018. Construction of the body work is mainly of aluminium and carbon fibre.\n\nThe design was developed by a team of Nissan's European and American designers and has been described as a \"car within a car\". The front and back sections are designed so they appear to be emerging from the bodywork. Key design elements include a redesigned rear section, stretched LED headlamps at the front, a power bulge on the hood, a lowered roof line and \"Samurai blade\" cooling ducts behind the front wheels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chucktannert/2018/12/13/why-does-the-nissan-gt-r50-cost-almost-a-million-bucks-more-than-a-stock-gt-r/|title=Why Does The Nissan GT-R50 Cost Almost A $1 Million More Than A Stock GT-R?|date=December 13, 2018|first=Chuck|last=Tannert|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=April 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===50th Anniversary Edition===\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150\">\n2020_Nissan_GT-R_50th_Anniversary_Edition_front_NYIAS_2019.jpg|\n2020_Nissan_GT-R_50th_Anniversary_Edition_rear_NYIAS_2019.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n[[Nissan]] introduced the 50th Anniversary Edition for 2020 at the 2019 [[New York Auto Show]]. The car has the {{convert|3799|cc|L cuin|1|abbr=on}} V6 [[Nissan VR engine|VR38DETT]] engine with {{convert|421|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,800 rpm and {{convert|633|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3,200-5,800 rpm. Nissan revealed the price of US$123,040 to the bayside blue, pearl white GT-R 50th Anniversary Edition and US$125,040 for the super silver GT-R 50th Anniversary Edition.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nNissan introduced two-tone exterior colours \u2013 bayside (wangan) blue, with white racing stripes, blue accents on the wheel spokes and pearl white with red stripes and super silver with white stripes also available for the 50th Anniversary Edition GT-R.\n\nThe 50th Anniversary Edition GT-R includes unique steering wheel and shift knob trim, special embossed seats, an [[Alcantara (material)|Alcantara]] headliner with unique stitching and Alcantara-wrapped sunvisors.<ref name=\"track-edition-2020\">{{Cite press release |url=https://usa.nissannews.com/en-US/releases/2020-nissan-gt-r-press-kit |title=2020 Nissan GT-R Press Kit |publisher=Nissan |location=US |date=2019-05-14 |access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Performance==\n[[File:Nissan GT-R MY2017 (1).jpg|thumb|Nissan GT-R (2017 facelift)]]\n\nNissan states the GT-R can attain a top speed of {{convert|196|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}},<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=123047#3 |title=Breaking News: Undisguised 2009 Nissan GT-R |accessdate=January 16, 2008 |work=edmunds.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024133643/http://www.edmunds.com/insideline/do/News/articleId=123047 |archivedate=October 24, 2007}}</ref> ''[[Motor Trend]]'' recorded a top speed of {{convert|195.0|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}}.<ref name=\"MTCompare\">{{cite web |url=https://www.motortrend.com/cars/nissan/gt-r/2009/2009-corvette-zr1-vs-porsche-gt2-vs-ferrari-599-vs-nissan-gtr/ |title=War of the Worlds: ZR1 vs GT2 vs 599 vs GT-R |accessdate=January 11, 2019 |last=St. Antoine |first=Arthur |date=October 27, 2008 |work=[[Motor Trend]] |publisher=Source Interlink Media}}</ref> In tests the original production model was shown to be capable of achieving 0-{{convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} times as low as 3.2&nbsp;seconds using \"launch control\".<ref name=\"MTCompare\"/> Owners expressed concern that duplicating the times achieved in these tests would void their factory warranty. Nissan's chief vehicle engineer Kazutoshi Mizuno has indicated that he has never used the term \"[[launch control (automotive)|launch control]]\", which refers to the act of turning off vehicle dynamic control (VDC) and launching the car at around 4,500 rpm.<ref name=mizuno>{{cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w1bHGaV-Lvw |title=2010 GT-R Launch Control Controversy Explained on video |publisher=GT Channel |access-date=April 19, 2019 |via=YouTube}}</ref> However, Nissan's director of product planning John Wiener stated in an interview with [[Jay Leno]] that \"we (Nissan) actually offer a 'launch mode'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5HwRZhPVmQ4 |title=Jay Leno's Garage: GT-R Review |accessdate=August 11, 2008 |publisher=YouTube}}</ref> The GT-R user's manual states that turning off the VDC is only meant for escaping low-traction situations such as mud or snow. Nissan has re-programmed the 2010 model year GT-R to reduce the engine speed at launch to around 3,000-3,500 rpm with VDC enabled, which is meant to improve acceleration times. The new programming was also installed on old 2009 vehicles still in Nissan's inventory, and is available for existing 2009 vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automotiveaddicts.com/2126/nissan-gt-r-launch-control-reprogram-clarification-from-nissan|title=Nissan GT-R Launch Control Reprogram Clarification from Nissan|date=January 30, 2009|first=Malcolm|last=Hogan|website=Automotiveaddicts.com|accessdate=April 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe updated GT-R now has a launch mode called \"R-Mode Start\". Pushing the three buttons up, includes the Transmission, Suspension and VDC the car gets to \"R-Mode Start\". The system allows a maximum of 4 consecutive hard launches before locking itself out, after which it can be unlocked by driving normally for {{cvt|1.5|mile|km|1|abbr=on|order=flip}}. The increased engine output of later models combined with the \"R-Mode Start\" has lowered the 0-{{convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} time to 2.7&nbsp;seconds.<ref name=\"MotorTrend2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/features/auto_news/2011/1111_2013_nissan_gt_r_10_second_car/|title=2013 Nissan GT-R is a 10 Second Car!}}</ref>\n''[[Motor Trend]]'' achieved a standing quarter-mile time of 11.6&nbsp;seconds at {{convert|120|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} using a US-spec 2009 model year GT-R.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/coupes/112_0803_2009_nissan_gtr_acceleration_test/acceleration_runs.html|title=2009 Nissan GT-R acceleration runs |publisher=Motortrend.com |date=February 26, 2007 |accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> [[Autocar (magazine)|''Autocar'']] achieved a 0-{{convert|100|mph|km/h|abbr=on|order=flip}} time of 8.5 seconds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XzEivL1Kruo|title=YouTube \u2013 Nissan GT-R &#124; BMW M3 [Autocar&#93; \u2013 Part 2 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=October 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe 2017 model year GT-R can accelerate to {{cvt|60|mph|km/h|order=flip|0}} in the same time of 2.7 seconds and achieve a {{convert|1/4|mile|m|round=5|order=flip|abbr=on}} time of 10.8 seconds at {{cvt|127|mph|km/h|order=flip|0}}. In 2017, the German car magazine [[Auto Bild]] tested the top speed of the 2017 model year GT-R and reached a top speed of {{cvt|328|km/h|mph|0}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ausfahrt.tv/youtuber-auto-bild-sportscars-328-kmh-pov-2017-nissan-gt-r-top-speed-autobahn-acceleration-auto-bild-sportscars/|title=Youtuber AUTO BILD SPORTSCARS: 328 km/h POV: 2017 Nissan GT-R Top Speed / Autobahn / Acceleration |work=Auto Bild Sportscars |language=German |via=Ausfahrt TV |access-date=April 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nissan GT-R cutmodel.JPG|thumb|right|Cutaway model showing rear mounted transmission]]\n\n'''Independent Lap Times'''\n\nTesting by ''[[Drivers Republic]]'' of a GT-R and 911 GT2 in stock form resulted in times of 7:56 minutes for the GT-R and 7:49 minutes for the GT2 respectively in partially damp conditions. While the tester had no doubt that the GT2 could achieve the factory time of 7:32 minutes, he couldn't imagine the customer GT-R going faster than 7:41 minutes in spite of the 7:29 minutes of factory claim.<ref name=\"DRtest\">{{cite web |url=http://magazines.drivers-republic.com/driversrepublic/thetruth030/ |title=The Truth |accessdate=November 27, 2008 |last=Harris |first=Chris |date=November 24, 2008 |work=Driver's Republic |page=23}}</ref>\n\nThe German magazine [[sport auto (Germany)|sport auto]] achieved a time of 7:50 minutes on the N\u00fcrburgring with a car supplied to them by [[Nissan]] during an initial short test in 2007 in partially damp condition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportauto-online.de/test_U_technik/fahrberichte/hxcms_article_508540_14469.hbs |title=Nissan GT-R: Ost-Erweiterung |accessdate=October 2, 2008 |work=sportauto |language=German}}</ref> In 2009, in a full \"super test\" ''sport auto'' achieved a time of 7:38 minutes on the N\u00fcrburgring with a standard GT-R driven by [[Horst von Saurma]],<ref name=\"SAringtime\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sportauto-online.de/supertest/nissan-gt-r-objektive-nordschleifen-rundezeit-des-486-ps-japaners-gtr-1347840.html |title=Objektive Nordschleifen-Rundezeit des Japaners |accessdate=July 16, 2009 |work=sportauto |language=German}}</ref> identical to a later \"super test\" [[Chevrolet Corvette (C6)|Corvette ZR1]] time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportauto-online.de/supertest/die-staerkste-corvette-zr1-im-supertest-auf-der-nordschleife-1415542.html |title=Corvette ZR1 im Supertest auf der Nordschleife: Was kann die st\u00e4rkste Corvette aller Zeiten? &#124; Sportauto |publisher=Sportauto-online.de |accessdate=December 19, 2009}}</ref> In a first test with the facelifted GT-R model, 'sport auto' recorded a lap time of 7:34 minutes on the N\u00fcrburgring with a standard GT-R driven by [[Horst von Saurma]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Horst von Saurma |url=http://www.sportauto-online.de/einzeltests/nissan-gt-r-2011-im-nordschleifen-test-mit-rundenzeit-3059911.html |title=Nissan GT-R 2011 im ersten Nordschleifen-Test \u2013 SPORT AUTO |publisher=Sportauto-online.de |date=April 22, 2011 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sport auto (Germany)|sport auto]] magazine tested the 2007 model year GT-R on the [[Hockenheimring]] circuit and recorded a lap time of 1:10.7 minutes during the \"supertest\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportauto-online.de/rundenzeiten-supertests-1062778.html|title=Rundenzeiten N\u00fcrburgring \u2013 SPORT AUTO|date=April 13, 2011|publisher=Sportauto-online.de|accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Nissan N\u00fcrburgring Lap Times'''\n\nIn 2009 Nissan claimed a lap time of 7:26.7 minutes with a 2009 model year GT-R on the base model's Dunlop tires<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2009/_STORY/090514-01-e.html|title=AWARD-WINNING NISSAN GT-R ACHIEVES NEW RECORD LAP TIME AT N\u00dcRBURGRING CIRCUIT|work=Nissan}}</ref> having previously set a time of 7:29&nbsp;minutes on standard Japanese market tires.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideline.com/nissan/gt-r/2009/fast-times-nissan-gt-r-sets-new-nurburgring-record.html|title=Fast Times: Nissan GT-R Sets New Nurburgring Record|accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan360.com/releases/release-2.php|title=Mengenal Pantai Lamaru Balikpapan - www.nissan360.com|date=October 13, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> [[Porsche]] has claimed Nissan overstated the GT-R's performance in September 2008.<ref name=\"PorscheAccusesNissan22\">{{cite web|url=http://carsguide.news.com.au/site/motoring-news/story/porsche_accuses_nissan_of_cheating_at_nurburgring/|title=Porsche accuses Nissan of cheating at N\u00fcrburgring|last=Gover|first=Paul|date=September 30, 2008|work=Carsguide.com.au|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=September 30, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle.aspx?AR=235197|title=Autocar \u2013 Porsche says Nissan cheating|publisher=Autocar.co.uk|accessdate=October 27, 2008}}</ref> Porsche claimed to have conducted a test of a factory stock, European market GT-R and achieved a slower time (of 7:54 minutes), apparently implying that the car isn't as fast around this public road as Nissan claims and/or that their driver isn't as talented as Nissan's. Nissan disputed the former and implied the latter claim in October 2008.<ref name=\"NissanDismisses22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2008/10/03/nissan-defends-gt-r-ring-time/|title=Nissan defends GT-R 'Ring time|last=Korzeniewski|first=Jeremy|date=October 3, 2008|work=[[Autoblog.com|Autoblog]]|accessdate=October 3, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"NissanRefutes22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2008/10/09/nissan-to-porsche-put-the-gt-r-down-before-you-hurt-yourself/|title=Nissan defends GT-R 'Ring time|last=Roth|first=Dan|date=October 9, 2008|work=[[Autoblog.com|Autoblog]]|accessdate=October 3, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2010, Nissan's sets a N\u00fcrburgring lap time using the 2011 model year GT-R with a new design. Driven by GT-R's development driver Toshio Suzuki. and the car set a lap time of 7:24.22 minutes.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HPW3w9HGQ7U|title=Nissan GT-R Nurburgring Nordschleife Lap Record|date=June 11, 2013|access-date=April 12, 2019|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"AutoGuide-2011-03-2422\">{{cite web|url=http://www.autoguide.com/auto-news/2011/03/2012-nissan-gt-r-724-22-nurburgring-lap-time-video.html|title=2012 Nissan GT-R 7:24.22 Nurburgring Lap Time Video|last=Wood|first=Colum|date=March 24, 2011|work=AutoGuide|location=Canada|access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Nissan the GT-R improved its N\u00fcrburgring lap time in October 2012 to 7:19.1 minutes by due to the 2014 model year improvements. This made it the 9th fastest ever production car around the N\u00fcrburgring at the time. Nissan claimed that it lost half a second in traffic, making a potential lap time of 7:18.6 minutes possible.<ref name=\"ma201422\">{{cite news|last=Vijayenthiran|first=Viknesh|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1080223_2014-nissan-gt-r-preview|title=2014 Nissan GT-R Revealed, Laps N\u00fcrburgring In 7:18: Video|date=November 2, 2012|work=Motor Authority|access-date=October 4, 2014|location=US}}</ref><ref name=\"CarAdvice201222\">{{cite news|last=Crawford|first=Anthony|url=http://www.caradvice.com.au/199112/2013-nissan-gt-r-sets-ninth-quickest-nurburgring-lap-time-in-history/|title=2013 Nissan GT-R sets ninth-quickest Nurburgring lap time in history|date=November 5, 2012|work=CarAdvice|access-date=October 4, 2014|location=Australia}}</ref>{{clear}}\n\n==Lap Records==\n;N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 220\n| image1 = Nissan_GT-R_Nismo_N_Attack_Package_front-left_2015_Nissan_Global_Headquarters_Gallery.jpg\n| image2 = Nissan_GT-R_Nismo_N_Attack_Package_rear-left_2015_Nissan_Global_Headquarters_Gallery.jpg\n| caption2 = 2015 Nissan GT-R NISMO [[Camouflaged]] Prototype revealed as the fastest road-legal volume production vehicle with a lap time of 7:08.679 minutes around the [[List of N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife lap times|Nurburgring Nordschleife]]\n| total_width =\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 =\n}}\n\nIn February 2013, [[Nissan]] opened the new [[Nismo|NISMO]] headquarters in [[Yokohama]]. Nissan's CEO [[Carlos Ghosn]] planned to introduce the GT-R NISMO within a year as the leading NISMO brand and attempt a production vehicle lap record at the [[List of N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife lap times|N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife]]. On May 18 development began, with Nissan's chief vehicle engineer Noboru Kaneko leading the joint NISMO and [[Dunlop Tyres]] effort to set the production vehicle lap record at the N\u00fcrburgring.\n\nOn June 26, the team started testing with standard GT-R's at [[Sendai Hi-Land Raceway]]. On July 16, the team visited the N\u00fcrburgring and collected data to aid development, and the team build the GT-R NISMO and it's aerodynamic development was finalized after testing it at the Sendai Raceway on July 24.\n\nOn September 2, the team returned to the N\u00fcrburgring with three GT-R NISMO cars and four drivers with two laps for each driver. drivers included [[Infiniti Red Bull Racing]] third driver [[S\u00e9bastien Buemi]], NISMO global brand ambassador and racer [[Michael Krumm]], German touring car driver [[Armin Hahne]], and a Japanese driver, [[Tetsuya Tanaka (racing driver)|Tetsuya Tanaka.]] team stopped all the tests of GT-R NISMO and on September 30, the team was aiming for a lap under 7:10 minutes, [[Armin Hahne]] and [[Tetsuya Tanaka (racing driver)|Tetsuya Tanaka]] didn't get close to the target record but [[S\u00e9bastien Buemi]] did a lap time of 7:12 minutes on his first lap, on his second lap he stopped to take some fuel out to reduce the weight. On the way to do a lap time under 7:10 minutes the car ran out of fuel. [[Michael Krumm]] did his first lap time of 7:10 minutes.\n\nAt 4:48 p.m just twelve minutes before the Nordschleife was scheduled to close, and five minutes before the rain, [[Michael Krumm]] did his second lap time of 7:08.679 minutes and achieved a peak speed of {{cvt|310|km/h|mph|0}} on the [[N\u00fcrburgring|Dottinger Hohe]] uphill climb, Nissan claimed it was the fastest road-legal volume production vehicle, and it was 11 seconds slower than the production vehicle lap record holder limited production [[Porsche 918 Spyder Weissach Package]]'s lap time of 6:57 minutes set earlier that month, making it the second fastest road-legal production vehicle around the track.\n\nAfter setting the lap time, the NISMO team invited the [[Car and Driver]]'s journalist Tony Quiroga to attempt the fastest lap time with a passenger at the N\u00fcrburgring Nordschleife. [[Michael Krumm]] drove the GT-R NISMO with the journalist and set a lap record for fastest production vehicle with a passenger around the track with a lap time of 7:19.46 minutes and {{cvt|303|km/h|mph|0}} on the [[N\u00fcrburgring|Dottinger Hohe]] uphill climb.<ref>{{Citation|last=\u65e5\u7523\u81ea\u52d5\u8eca\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|title=Michael Krumm Attacks N\u00fcrburgring in a Nissan GT-R NISMO|date=November 19, 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sNAT_c3CLHw|access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://europe.nissannews.com/en-GB/releases/nissan-gt-r-nismo-earns-its-wings-at-the-ring|title=Nissan GT-R Nismo earns its wings at the`Ring|date=2013-11-19|website=NISSAN NEWS|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=NISSAN GT-R NISMO Development Story (REVISED)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YDXoFK_kGJQ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"C&D First Ride\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/a15113029/2015-nissan-gt-r-nismo-track-package-first-ride-review|title=We Survived Godzilla (And Possibly Set a New 'Ring Record): Our Wicked Ride in the 2015 Nissan GT-R NISMO Track Package|last=Quiroga|first=Tony|date=2014-01-07|website=Car and Driver|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=2015 Nissan GT-R NISMO Track Package - Record Nurburging Passenger Lap?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z6M8X26-BOo|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n;Goodwood Hill Climb\n[[File:Nissan_GT-R_Nismo_'Time_Attack'_Edition_at_Goodwood_2014_003.jpg|alt=|thumb|220x220px|2015 Nissan GT-R NISMO [[Camouflaged]] Prototype set a new road-legal production vehicle record of 49.27 seconds around the [[Goodwood Festival of Speed|Goodwood]] uphill climb.]]\n\nOn June 2014, the Nissan GT-R NISMO was revealed at the [[Goodwood Festival of Speed|Goodwood Festival]]. The car ran on the Goodwood Hill climb, driven by [[Jann Mardenborough]], set a time of 49.27 seconds, making it the fastest road-legal production vehicle up the hill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autoevolution.com/news/2015-nissan-gt-r-nismo-time-attack-sets-record-at-goodwood-video-83250.html|title=2015 Nissan GT-R Nismo Time Attack Sets Record at Goodwood|last=Ross|first=Jeffrey|date=2014-07-01|website=autoevolution|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n;N\u00fcrburgring GP 5.15 km Course\n\nOn August 13, 2014, German car magazine [[Sport auto (Germany)|Sport Auto]] tested the 2015 model year GT-R NISMO at the [[N\u00fcrburgring|Nurburgring GP 5.15 km circuit]], driven by [[Christian Gebhardt]], set a new road-legal production vehicle lap record around the track with a 2:13.80 minutes of lap time.<ref>{{Citation|title=0-300 km/h Nissan GT-R Nismo & N\u00fcrburgring GP Test sport auto|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4rl8gF9YA8k|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n;Willow Springs\n\nOn September, 2014, ''[[Motor Trend]]'' conducted a test using the 2015 model year Nissan GT-R NISMO at [[Willow Springs International Motorsports Park|Willow Springs - Street of Willow]] circuit. The test driver  [[Randy Pobst]] set a lap time of 1:19.07 minutes and making it the fastest road-legal production vehicle around track. The 2014 model year GT-R Track Edition lapped in 1:19.55 minutes and took the second place, 2012 model year GT-R Premium lapped in 1:20.25 minutes and took the third place of the road-legal production vehicle lap records around track. On February, 2015, ''[[Motor Trend]]'' tested a comaprison with the GT-R NISMO and the [[Chevrolet Corvette (C7)|Corvette C7 Z06]], On the track test, test driver Randy Pobst drove the GT-R NISMO at [[Willow Springs International Motorsports Park|Willow Springs Circuit]] set a new road-legal production vehicle lap record around the track at the time with a lap time of 1:25.70 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.planet-9.com/threads/motor-trend-streets-of-willow-lap-times-1-6-mi.176538/|title=Motor Trend: Streets of Willow lap times (1.6 mi)|website=Planet-9 Porsche Forum|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fastestlaps.com/tests/iz8l4ib8l90t|title=Nissan GT-R Nismo laptime at Willow Springs - Streets of Willow|website=FastestLaps.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B7P4nJzD-4s&feature=player_detailpage|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motortrend.com/cars/nissan/gt-r/2015/2015-chevrolet-corvette-z06-vs-2015-nissan-gt-r-nismo-comparison/amp/|title=https://www.motortrend.com \u203a ... 2015 Chevrolet Corvette Z06 vs. 2015 Nissan GT-R Nismo ... - MotorTrend|last=Scott|first=Evans|date=February 5, 2015|website=Motor Trend|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n;Tsukuba Circuit\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 220\n| image1 = Osaka Auto Messe 2018 (420) - Nissan GT-R NISMO (DBA-R35) Ver.CAR TOP TSUKUBA TIME ATTACK.jpg\n| image2 = Osaka Auto Messe 2018 (421) - Nissan GT-R NISMO (DBA-R35) Ver.CAR TOP TSUKUBA TIME ATTACK.jpg\n| caption2 = 2017 Nissan GT-R NISMO [[Tsukuba Circuit]] time attack vehicle set the fastest road-legal production vehicle lap record of 1:00.293 minutes.\n| total_width =\n| alt1 =\n| caption1 =\n}}\n\nOn December 8, 2017, in a test conducted by [[Nissan]] for 50th anniversary of the GT-R, a 2018 model year Nissan GT-R NISMO, driven by Kazuo Shimizu, set a lap time of 1.00.293 minutes on the [[Tsukuba Circuit]] \u2013 making it the fastest road-legal production vehicle around the track at the time.<ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_NZDeaEwl6Q|title=\u3010GT-R NISMO\u3011\u30ab\u30fc\u30c8\u30c3\u30d7\u7b51\u6ce2\u30a2\u30bf\u30c3\u30af / Tsukuba Attack|date=2018-01-11|publisher=Nissan|trans-title=\u3010GT-R NISMO\u3011 Car Top Tsukuba Attack|location=Japan|access-date=2019-06-25|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZSJtyjWfvWQ|title=\u3010GT-R NISMO\u3011\u30ab\u30fc\u30c8\u30c3\u30d7\u7b51\u6ce2\u30a2\u30bf\u30c3\u30af\u8eca\u8f09 / Tsukuba Attack Incar|date=2018-01-11|publisher=Nissan|trans-title=\u3010GT-R NISMO\u3011 Car Top Tsukuba Attack In Car|location=Japan|access-date=2019-06-25|via=YouTube}}</ref> On December 9, 2019 [[Nissan]] again broke the own record of the fastest road-legal production vehicle around the track using a 2020 model year Nissan GT-R NISMO, driven by [[Tsugio Matsuda]], set a lap time of 59.361 seconds.<ref>{{Citation|title=\u3010\u52d5\u753b\u3011NISSAN GT-R NISMO 2020 \u7b51\u6ce2\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0\u30a2\u30bf\u30c3\u30af \u307e\u3068\u3081\u52d5\u753b|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e6LCbMKjoMM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=\u3010\u52d5\u753b\u3011NISSAN GT-R NISMO 2020 \u7b51\u6ce2\u30bf\u30a4\u30e0\u30a2\u30bf\u30c3\u30af \u30aa\u30f3\u30dc\u30fc\u30c9\u6620\u50cf|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EBNuvmmrgq0|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\n;INTA Circuit\n\nIn 2018, [[Nissan]] conducted a test on the INTA Circuit in Spain, driven by [[Marc Gen\u00e9]] with a 2017 model year GT-R NISMO, GT-R Track Edition and a GT-R Premium. The GT-R NISMO set a new road-legal production vehicle lap record around track with a lap time of 1:05.83 minutes. The GT-R Track Edition lapped in 1:06.39 minutes and took the second place, GT-R Premium lapped in 1:06.93 minutes and took the third place of the road-legal production vehicle lap records around track.<ref>{{Cite press release|url=https://cornwallnissan.ca/news/GT-R+and+NISMO+ambassador+Marc+GenC3A9+set+record+in+Spain/24561/|title=GT-R and NISMO ambassador Marc Gen\u00e9 set record in Spain|publisher=Cornwall Nissan|location=Canada|date=June 8, 2020|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==Motorsport==\n\n===Super GT===\n[[File:No.12 CALSONIC IMPUL GT-R at SUZUKA 1000km THE FINAL (8).jpg|thumb|right|Nissan GT-R GT500 of Impul competing at the Suzuka 1000 km in 2017]]\n[[NISMO]], the [[motorsport]] arm of Nissan, entered the Nissan GT-R in the [[Super GT]] race series in the GT500 class for the 2008 season, replacing the [[Nissan 350Z|350Z]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nismo.co.jp/M_SPORTS/news/070009.html |title=\u300cNISSAN GT-R\u300d\u304c SUPER GT \u306b\u53c2\u6226 |trans-title=\"NISSAN GT-R\" participates in SUPER GT |publisher=Nissan Motorsports |language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nThe 2008 GT500 version of the car has a completely different drivetrain compared to the production car. The race car is upgraded to a [[Nissan VK engine#VK45DE|VK45DE]] 4.5-litre naturally aspirated<ref>Racecar Engineering 2010 Vol.20 No.8, p. 14-20.</ref> [[V8 engine|V8]] instead of the twin-turbocharge [[VR38DETT]] V6 engine. It uses a 6 speed sequential [[manual transmission|manual]] gearbox and a rear-wheel-drive layout from its predecessor, the [[Nissan 350Z|350Z]] race car.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/Nissan-GT-R/230696/ |title=Meet the V8 Nissan GT-R |publisher=Autocar |date=January 31, 2008 |accessdate=November 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927124908/http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/Nissan-GT-R/230696/ |archivedate=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Safety Car 2008 Super GT.jpg|left|thumb|The GT-R safety car leading a pack of cars at the [[Super GT]] race at [[Fuji Speedway]] in May 2008.]]\n\nA prototype was spotted testing around the [[Suzuka Circuit]] as well as [[Fuji Speedway]] in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagtroc.org/gallery/thumbnails.php?album=56|title=NAGTROC gallery \u2013 Super GT GT-R|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409124707/http://www.nagtroc.org/gallery/thumbnails.php?album=56|archivedate=April 9, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtr-world.net/photogallery/racecars/gtr-production-race-car.html |title=404 |website=www.gtr-world.net |accessdate=November 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213133933/http://www.gtr-world.net/photogallery/racecars/gtr-production-race-car.html |archivedate=December 13, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The car went on to win the opening race of the [[2008 Super GT Series|2008 Super GT season]] at Suzuka scoring a one-two finish for Nissan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supergt.net/supergt/2008/0801/0801racv_e.htm |title=Super GT 2008 Round 1 Suzuka Race Review |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412000528/http://supergt.net/supergt/2008/0801/0801racv_e.htm |archivedate=April 12, 2008}}</ref> The dominant performances in the opening race has led to all GT-Rs being applied a 50&nbsp;kg weight penalty in addition to the race weight penalty under the Special Adjustment of Performance under the Super GT regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supergt.net/supergt/2008/0803/0803test_e.htm?1v |title=Super GT 2008 Fuji Official Test |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080415090154/http://supergt.net/supergt/2008/0803/0803test_e.htm?1v |archivedate=April 15, 2008}}</ref> In race two, the GT-R repeated their 1\u20132 result in Suzuka despite the race winning car of team [[NISMO]] carrying a 100&nbsp;kg weight penalty making it only the 3rd team in JGTC/Super GT history to do so. The last time this feat was achieved was 10 years ago by NISMO Skyline GT-R racing under the same number 23.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supergt.net/supergt/2008/0802/0802racv_e.htm |title=Super GT 2008 Round 2 Okayama Race Review |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423112145/http://supergt.net/supergt/2008/0802/0802racv_e.htm |archivedate=April 23, 2008}}</ref> Despite the weight handicap, it won the drivers' championship in the [[2008 Super GT Series|2008 season]] through the Xanavi NISMO GT-R driven by [[Satoshi Motoyama]] and [[Beno\u00eet Tr\u00e9luyer]], though they only came third in the teams' championship. It also won 7 out of 9 races driven by 4 different teams using GT-Rs.[[File:Satoshi Motoyama 2014 Super GT Suzuka Race.jpg|thumb|right|Nissan GT-R Nismo GT500 of Mola in the [[2014 Super GT season]]]]The GT500 version scored 4 victories in the 2009 Japanese SUPER GT Series GT 500 class.\n\nIn 2010, the VK45DE 4.5-litre engine was replaced by a newly developed 3.4-litre engine ([[Nissan VRH35 engine#Specification of VRH34A|VRH34A]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan-motorsports.com/ENN/PRESS/2010/100210.html |title=2010 Press Release |publisher=Nissan Motorsports |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt also is the 2011 and 2012 Champion. Team Mola GT-R with drivers [[Ronnie Quintarelli]] and [[Masataka Yanagida]] got back to back championships in both Team and Driver in the Super GT500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supergt.net/|title=SUPER GT.net \u2013 SUPER GT OFFICIAL WEBSITE|publisher=|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, the Super GT regulations were aligned with those of the [[Deutsche Tourenwagen Masters]], and so the V8 engine was replaced with a 2.0-litre, 4-cylinder turbocharged engine.<ref>[[2014 Super GT season]]</ref>\n\n===FIA GT/GT1 World Championship===\n[[File:Nissan GT-R GT1 Sumo Power GT 20 Silverstone 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Sumo Power's Nissan GT-R competing in the [[FIA GT1 World Championship]] at the 2011 Silverstone round]]\n\nOn February 27, 2009, [[NISMO]] announced a partnership with British racing team Gigawave Motorsports to enter a GT-R in four races in the [[2009 FIA GT Championship season]]. The entry did not compete for championship points, but was used by NISMO to refine the performance of the GT-R for future customer teams to use the car in the planned [[FIA GT1 World Championship]] in 2010. NISMO driver [[Michael Krumm]] and Gigawave driver [[Darren Turner]] would co-drive the GT1 GT-R.<ref name=\"FIA GT\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fiagt.com/newsitem.php?key=1914 | title = 2009 Nismo \u2013 Gigawave Motorsport announcement | publisher=[[FIA GT Championship]] | date = February 27, 2009 | accessdate = February 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sumo Power]] GT-R won the [[2010 RAC Tourist Trophy]] at [[Silverstone Circuit]] as part of the FIA GT1 World Championship on May 2, 2010.\n\nThe [[2011 FIA GT1 World Championship season|2011 season]] saw [[Swiss Racing Team]] switch to [[Lamborghini]] which left Sumo Power running four GT-Rs, two under the Sumo Power GT name and two under JR Motorsports. JR Motorsports with the drivers [[Michael Krumm]] and [[Lucas Luhr]] won the Drivers Championship for the 2011 season, gaining 3 wins and 1 pole position in 10 races.\n\n====GT-R Nismo GT1====\nDesigned and produced specifically to compete in the [[FIA GT1 World Championship]], the GT-R NISMO GT1 is based on the road-going version of the Nissan GT-R. The GT-R NISMO GT1 is powered by a NISMO race-prepped [[Nissan VK engine#VK56DE|VK56DE]], a naturally aspirated V8 engine that displaces 5,552 cc. It measures 80.3inches in width, 186.2 inches in length, and has a wheelbase of 109.4 inches.<ref>[http://www.rpmpromotions.com/GT1andGT3techspec.pdf] http://www.rpmpromotions.com/GT1andGT3techspec.pdf.</ref>\n* Displacement: DOHC naturally aspirated [[V8 engine|V8 front mid-engine]] {{convert|5552|cc|L cuin|1|abbr=on}}\n* Power output: {{convert|441|kW|PS hp PS|abbr=on|disp=out|0}} (capped \u2013 GT1 regulations)\n* Valves Per Cylinder: 4\n* Torque: {{convert|479.35|lbft|abbr=on|order=flip}}\n* Drivetrain: [[Rear-wheel drive]]\n* [[Curb weight]]: {{convert|1250|kg|0|abbr=on}} (as per GT1 regulations)\n* Transmission: [[Ricardo plc|Ricardo]] 6-speed transaxle, sequential shift lever, 5.5-inch carbon triple-plate clutch\n* Suspension: Adjustable suspension with double wishbones front and multi-link rear\n* Brakes: [[Brembo]] 6-piston calipers with carbon discs and pads\n* Tyres: Front and rear [[Michelin]] 31/71-18 (GT1 controlled specification)\n\n====GT-R Nismo GT3====\n\n[[File:Chiyo Reip Strauss 2015 Bathurst 12 Hour winner.JPG|thumb|A GT-R won the [[2015 Liqui Moly Bathurst 12 Hour]] driven by [[Katsumasa Chiyo]], Wolfgang Reip and Florian Strauss]]\n[[File:No.11 GAINER TANAX GT-R after 2019 Suzuka 300km (1).jpg|thumb|A GT-R won the [[2019 Super GT Series|Suzuka 300km]] driven by [[Katsuyuki Hiranaka]] and [[Hironobu Yasuda]]]]\n\nThe GT-R NISMO GT3 is powered by the [[Nissan VR engine|VR38DETT]], a twin-turbocharged V6 engine that displaces 3,799 cc. It measures 80.15 inches in width, 188.19 inches in length, and has a wheelbase of 109.45 inches.<ref>[http://www.nismo.co.jp/en/products/GT3/spec.html]. http://www.nismo.co.jp/en/products/GT3/spec.html</ref>\n* Displacement: DOHC twin-turbocharged [[V6 engine|V6 front mid-engine]] {{convert|3799|cc|L cuin|1|abbr=on}}\n* Power output: {{Convert|447|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm\n* Valves Per Cylinder: 4\n* Torque: {{convert|510|lbft|abbr=on|order=flip|0}} at 5,000&nbsp;rpm\n* Drivetrain: Premium Midship [[Rear-wheel drive|RWD]]\n* [[Curb weight]]: {{convert|1300|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n* Brakes: Front: 6-piston caliper Rear: 4-piston caliper\n* [[Automobile drag coefficient|Drag coefficient]]: 0.26\n* Transmission: Six-speed sequential racing transmission in transaxle configuration with multi-disc limited-slip differential and traction control\n* Suspension: Adjustable suspension with double wishbones front and multi-link rear\n* Extras: Semi-automatic paddle-shift\n* Tyres: Front: 330/710-18, Rear: 330/710-18\n* Top speed: {{cvt|182-205|mph|kph|0|abbr=on|order=flip}} depending on gearing ratio.\n\nGT-R GT3 won the [[2015 Liqui Moly Bathurst 12 Hour]] driven by [[Katsumasa Chiyo]], Wolfgang Reip and Florian Strauss. The NISMO team returned to the [[Mount Panorama Circuit]] for the [[2016 Liqui Moly Bathurst 12 Hour]] where after qualifying a disappointing 13th, Chiyo, Strauss and Nissan Australia's [[Rick Kelly]] finished in second place, only 1.3 seconds behind the race winning [[McLaren 650S#GT3|McLaren 650S GT3]] from [[Tekno Autosports]]. The [[Nismo Global Driver Exchange|NISMO Athlete Global Team]] led the most number of laps in the race having led for 107 of the 297 laps run.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bartholomaeus|first=Stefan|url=http://www.speedcafe.com/2016/02/07/svg-leads-mclaren-to-bathurst-12-hour-victory/|title=SVG leads McLaren to Bathurst 12 Hour victory|date=February 7, 2016|work=Speedcafe|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, a GT-R GT3 won the championship at the [[Blancpain Endurance Series]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://usa.nissannews.com/en-US/channels/channel-1609|title=FIA World Endurance Championship|website=Nissan News USA|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, it won in all six races for the [[Blancpain Endurance Series|Super Endurance Series]], easily winning the series championship. At the Total [[24 Hours of Spa]], the car finished all the races consecutively 4 years in a row between 2014 and 2017, as well as finishing [[24 Hours N\u00fcrburgring|24 Hours Nurburgring]] consecutively between 2014 and 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nismo.co.jp/en/coprofile/history.html|title=NISMO {{!}} MAJOR ACHIEVEMENTS|website=www.nismo.co.jp|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gtr-registry.com/en-r35-gtr-nismo-gt3.php|title=Nissan GT-R R35: Nismo GT3|website=gtr-registry.com|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n===Other categories===\n\nA production-based GT-R made its world motorsport debut in Australia's [[Targa Tasmania]] tarmac [[rallying|rally]] in April 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.targa.com.au/Media/Releases/GTR.html |title=Nissan GT-R confirms Targa Appearance 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113211321/http://www.targa.com.au/Media/Releases/GTR.html |archivedate=January 13, 2008}}</ref> however it sustained damage early in the event and did not complete the rally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rallyresults.com.au/targa2008/Modern.pdf|title=2008 Targa Tasmania Modern Competition results}}</ref> Later in 2008 a GT-R won the Competition Modern class in the [[Targa West]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.targawest.com.au/Portals/0/docs/CMM08_RESULTSFORLEG_QUITTARGAWEST.PDF|title=2008 Targa West Modern Competition results}}</ref> before returning to Targa Tasmania in 2009 to take the outright win in the Modern class.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportcom.com.au/targatasmania/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=1&limit=1&limitstart=0&Itemid=59 |title=Targa Wrest Point all go and filling fast |date=May 15, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503033500/http://www.sportcom.com.au/targatasmania/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=1&limit=1&limitstart=0&Itemid=59 |archivedate=May 3, 2009}}</ref> In 2009 Nissan's GT-R won the [[One Lap of America]] competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onelapofamerica.com/history/2009/results/showResults.shtml?y=2009&res=OVL_CUM |title=the Official Webpage |publisher=One Lap of America |accessdate=July 7, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510091549/http://www.onelapofamerica.com/history/2009/results/showResults.shtml?y=2009&res=OVL_CUM |archivedate=May 10, 2009}}</ref> In 2010 the GT-R finished 2nd over all in the [[One Lap of America]] competition.\n\nDuring the 2010 [[SCCA World Challenge]] season, a pair of GT class GT-Rs were campaigned by Brass Monkey Racing and driven by Steve Ott and Tony Rivera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://octanereport.com/tuned-cars/2010/06/04/feature-brass-monkey-racing-world-challenge-r35-nissan-gt-r.html |title=Feature \u2013 Brass Monkey Racing World Challenge R35 Nissan GT-R |publisher=The Octane Report |accessdate=June 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2010, [[NISMO]] announced a Club Track Edition<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nismo.co.jp/omori_factory/news_list/news_0604.html|title=NISMO &#124; Omori Factory News|website=www.nismo.co.jp}}</ref> GT-R available via its [[Nissan]] supported Omori aftermarket factory. This domestic market trim is a non-street legal, race ready variant equipped with a 6-point roll cage and upgraded with NISMO race package developed through its Tokachi endurance racer program.\n\nOn June 25 and 26, 2011, the No. 71 Schulze Motorsport Nissan GT-R took part in the [[24 Hours of N\u00fcrburgring#2011 race|24 Hours of N\u00fcrburgring 2011]] driven by Michael Schulze, Tobias Schulze, [[Kazunori Yamauchi]] and Yasuyoshi Yamamoto. The car finished the race in 36th place overall, achieving a victory in the SP 8T class after overcoming several technical problems.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}} It was the first time a Nissan GT-R took part in the 24 Hours of N\u00fcrburgring. In the following year, Nissan participated the SP8T class with 2 Club Track Edition GT-Rs as works team, which driven by Team Nissan and Team [[Gran Turismo (series)|GT Academy]], both cars completed the race in 99th and 30th in overall respectively \u2013 through they are the only entries in SP-8T class that year.{{Clear}}\n\n==Aftermarket tuning==\n{{summarize section|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Tuning===\n\nDespite early concerns about the difficulty of modifying the Nissan GT-R, many aftermarket tuning parts have become available. The previously reported \"untuneable\" [[Engine control unit|ECU]] has since been hacked by several tuning houses.\n\n[[COBB Tuning]] was the first company to access the GT-R's encrypted ECU.<ref name=\"motortrend1\">{{cite web |url=http://wot.motortrend.com/cobb-tuning-cracks-nissan-gtrs-encrypted-ecu-308.html |title=Cobb Tuning cracks Nissan GT-R\u2019s encrypted ECU|publisher=Motortrend.com|date=April 9, 2008|accessdate=May 29, 2012}}</ref> With their AccessPORT anyone can reprogram both the engine and transmission control units with off the shelf or custom maps. [[Mine's]] also has limited control of the ECU, and others (MCR,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcr-ltd.com/demo.html |script-title=ja:\u30bb\u30f3\u30c8\u30e9\u30eb:\uff2e\uff45\uff57\u3000\u65e5\u7523\u3000\uff27\uff34\uff0d\uff32 |language=Japanese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214015507/http://www.mcr-ltd.com/demo.html |archivedate=December 14, 2007}}</ref> [[HKS (company)|HKS]], and Top Secret) have bypassed the unit. They have been seen testing modified GT-Rs with the former two having conducted tests at the [[Tsukuba Circuit]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Option Fans Magazine |publisher=Unity Media Communications |date=February 2008 |issue=78 |pages=12, 56}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Option Fans Magazine |date=July 2008 |issue=78 |pages=12, 56}}</ref>\n\nEcutek tuning on the other hand was the first company to manipulate and change shift points on the GT-R in the TCM (Transmission Control Module) on automatic mode. This can be done at will by the driver. Ecutek also allows the driver to adjust launch control on the fly available with a wrap around boost gauge that can read over 20 PSI.<ref name=\"gtrlife1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gtrlife.com/forums/topic/77896-ecutek-paving-the-way-with-adjustable-shiftpoints-in-automode/ |title=Ecutek tuning paving the way with adjustable shiftpoints in automode|publisher=gtrlife.com|date=November 14, 2012|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> Like [[COBB Tuning]], Ecutek currently offers engine tuning on the ECU and TCM with different launch control software from LC1 up to LC5.<ref name=\"gtrlife2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gtrlife.com/forums/topic/69896-now-offering-staged-ecutek-flashes-w-cable-e85-package-available/ |title=Now offering Ecutek Staged Ecutek flashes with cable/E85 Package available|publisher=gtrlife.com|date=November 18, 2012|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref>\nOn January 16, 2013, Ecutek also became the first company to construct and offer Flex Fuel hardware and software capability for all Nissan GT-Rs. This fuel kit requires the Ecutek specific TCM. The kit provides changes in the cold start cranking compensation, changes to the maximum target boost, changes in the ignition timing, changes to target airflow, changes in cam timing, and changes in the fuel economy gauge reading all based solely on ethanol content in the gas tank.<ref name=\"gtrlife3\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gtrlife.com/forums/topic/80414-ecutek-flex-fuel-is-reality/ |title=Ecutek Flex Fuel is Reality!|publisher=gtrlife.com|date=January 16, 2013|accessdate=March 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJapan based tuner Mine's has created the [[VR38DETT]] super response engine which uses lightened engine internals like titanium rods, lightened pistons and many other components that allow the engine to rev more quickly, it makes {{convert|800|PS|kW hp PS|0|abbr=on|disp=out}}.<ref name=\"gtrblog1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gtrblog.com/2010/01/17/mines-meeting-event-2010-mines-dry-carbon-front-bumper-for-nissan-gtr-scoop/ |title=Mine\u2019s Meeting Event: Mine\u2019s GT-R |publisher=gtrblog.com|date=January 17, 2010|accessdate=May 29, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"motorauthority1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1025768_mines-shows-off-latest-gt-r-package-at-tokyo-auto-salon |title=Mine\u2019s shows off latest GT-R package at Tokyo Auto Salon|publisher=motorauthority.com|date=January 14, 2009|accessdate=May 29, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAMS Performance, Alpha Logic Performance and Extreme Turbo Systems all build drag cars and aftermarket tuner parts for the Nissan GT-R.\n\nIn a review by ''[[Motor Trend]]'' editor Scott Kanemura, it was revealed that the GPS system fitted to the GT-R would remove the {{cvt|180|km/h|mph|0}} [[speed limiter]] when the car arrives at a race track, but only on tracks approved by Nissan. Aftermarket ECUs have been developed to bypass the speed limiter, in addition to stand-alone speed-limiter defeaters. The GPS check will not be implemented in American models.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2008/02/07/nissan-gt-r-cant-take-aftermarket-wheels-unapproved-race-track/2 |title=Nissan GT-R can't take aftermarket wheels, unapproved race tracks are out |publisher=Auto Blog |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080211114547/http://www.autoblog.com/2008/02/07/nissan-gt-r-cant-take-aftermarket-wheels-unapproved-race-track/2 |archivedate=February 11, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, Nissan's official motorsport and tuning arm [[Nismo|NISMO]] announced the \"Club Sport\" tuning package for the GT-R . The package, which is also fitted to the SpecV,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nismo.co.jp/news_list/2008/news_flash/080005.html |title=NISMO NEWS RELEASE |language=Japanese}}</ref> includes [[Bilstein Shock Absorbers|Bilstein]] Damptronic compatible dampers, 20\" forged aluminum wheels from [[Rays Engineering|RAYS Engineering]], [[Bridgestone]] [[run-flat tire]]s, [[Recaro]] carbon fiber-shelled bucket seats, a titanium exhaust, and a revised rear diffuser with an added cooling duct.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nismo.co.jp/news_list/2008/news_flash/080005_1.html |title=NISMO NEWS RELEASE |language=Japanese}}</ref> The package is supported by a warranty and saves over {{convert|20|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}.\n\n===Drag Racing===\n\nAMS Performance, based in [[West Chicago, Illinois|West Chicago Illinois]], has set record power levels and performance numbers for the GT-R. Their Alpha Omega GT-R as well as the first GT-R to reach the 9's, 8's, and 7's. In June 2013, OMEGA broke into the 7s when it ran a 7.98 at 299.56 km/h (186.14 mph). During the evening of the 7 second pass Omega broke a couple of other records. Omega bested its previous 97\u2013209 km/h (60\u2013130 mph) time with 2.67 seconds. Omega also broke the 161\u2013241 km/h (100\u2013150 mph) record which was previously held by an Underground Racing TT Gallardo (2.58 seconds) with 2.45 seconds. But in June 2015, the Alpha Omega GT-R get generating over 2050 whp and boasts 0\u201360 mph time of 1.49 seconds. Omega set multiple world records at the WannaGoFast 1/2 Mile Shootout at Built Field Airport in Monee, Illinois which included: 361.8 km/h (224.91 mph) in a standing 1/2 mile; 97\u2013209 km/h (60\u2013130 mph) time in 2.28 seconds; 0\u2013161 km/h (0\u2013100 mph) in 2.78 seconds; 0\u2013300 km/h (0\u2013186 mph) in 7.07 seconds; 0\u2013322 km/h (0\u2013200 mph) in 10.49 seconds. the Alpha Omega GT-R did it's best of quarter mile time in 7.49 seconds at 310 km/h (193 mph). making it the quickest and fastest GT-R and road-legal vehicle in the world. and the car won the King Of The Streets competition two times in the row. The AMS Performance Alpha Omega package functions more as a shop/research and development vehicle which is the reason why it is not available to the general public. However, anybody can purchase the Alpha 6, Alpha 9, Alpha 10, Alpha 12, Alpha 14, Alpha 16 and Alpha X packages; each respectively with approximately 600, 900, 1000, 1200, 1,400, 1,600, 2,200 wheel horsepower when installed and tuned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amsperformance.com/project/alpha-omega-gtr/|title=Alpha Omega GTR|website=AMSPerformance.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/03/24/nissans-new-speedster-zooms-from-zero-to-60-in-1-53-seconds/|title=This car zooms from zero to 60 in 1.53 seconds (and it\u2019s street legal)|last=Steinbuch|first=Yaron|date=2015-03-24|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 AMS Performance build a GT-R calls Alpha-G GT-R and the car will been the first Nissan GT-R to do a quarter mile in 6 seconds. Car ran it from 6.937 seconds driven by Gidi Chamdi with a trap speed of 315.36 km/h (196 mph) and holded the fastest AWD record.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amsperformance.com/alpha-g-the-road-to-6-part-2/|title=Alpha Performance Alpha G r35 GT-R World Record First into the 6's and quickest awd car ever|date=2017-04-01|website=AMSPerformance.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> But Later ETS (Extreme Turbo Systems) GT-R broke the record with a 6.88 seconds of quarter mile pass at 358.80 km/h (223 mph). And it's became as the world's fastest car at a standing half mile with trap speed of 410.29 km/h (255 mph).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/a12474969/3000-hp-nissan-gt-r-nearly-wrecks-while-setting-world-record/|title=Watch This 3000-HP Nissan GT-R Nearly Wreck While Breaking a 1/4-Mile World Record|last=Silvestro|first=Brian|date=2017-09-26|website=Road & Track|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, the Alpha Logic Performance from [[Dubai]] set the quarter-mile record for fastest GT-R and fastest AWD using their \"Panda\" GT-R in 6.582 seconds at {{cvt|373.82|km/h|mph}}.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.autoevolution.com/news/nissan-gt-r-sets-1-4-mile-world-record-with-astounding-65s-pass-131585.html |title=UPDATE: Nissan GT-R Sets 1/4-Mile World Record with Astounding 6.5s Pass |last=Tutu |first=Andrei |website=autoevolution |date=2019-01-13 |access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/a26360219/alpha-logic-nissan-gt-r-quarter-mile-record-video/ |title=Watch This Impossibly Quick Nissan GT-R Break a Quarter-Mile Record |last=Silvestro |first=Brian |website=Road & Track |date=2019-02-16 |access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref>But in 2019 Import vs Domestic finals the 3500 whp and 100 PSI of boost ETS-G GT-R broke the quickest and fastest GT-R, AWD and  Stock Unibody world record. Car ran the 1/4 mile in 6.56 seconds and a trap speed of 362.02 km/h (225 mph). And won the competition by beating the Alpha Queen GT-R which is ran a 6.87 second quarter mile.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roadandtrack.com/motorsports/a29813358/ets-nissan-gt-r-drag-car-world-record-656-225-mph/|title=This 6.56-Second Record-Breaking Nissan GT-R Drag Car Makes 100 PSI of Boost|last=Silvestro|first=Brian|date=2019-11-18|website=Road & Track|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = vertical\n| width = 220\n| image1 = \u042e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e Nissan GT-R (R35) Mk.2 AMS Alpha 12+ (2).jpg\n| image2 = \u042e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e Nissan GT-R (R35) Mk.2 AMS Alpha 12+.jpg\n| caption2 = World's fastest road-legal 1 mile record holder Nissan GT-R AMS Alpha 12+\n| total_width = \n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n}}\n\nAt the [[Dragtimes]] Competition, Russia, the AMS Alpha 12 GT-R broke the fastest road-legal standing 1 mile record driven by Jury with a trap speed of 382 km/h (237 mph) but later the record broken by a 2500 whp [[Ford GT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=nissam+gtr+ams+alpga+12+1+mile+world+record&oq=nissam+gtr+ams+alpga+12+1+mile+world+record&aqs=chrome..69i57.18292j0j4&client=ms-android-samsung&sourceid=chrome-mobile&ie=UTF-8#|title=nissam gtr ams alpga 12 1 mile world record - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Later in the same competition, Switzer Goliath GT-R broke the quickest road-legal standing 1 mile record in 22.602 seconds with a trap speed of 402 km/h (250 mph).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=switzer+goliath+gtr+world+record&oq=switzer+goliatj+gtr+world+r&aqs=chrome.1.69i57j33.9166j0j4&client=ms-android-samsung&sourceid=chrome-mobile&ie=UTF-8#|title=switzer goliath gtr world record - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topgear.com/car-news/video/switzer-gt-r-hits-250mph|title=Switzer GT-R hits 250mph|date=2013-10-22|website=Top Gear|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Time Attack===\n\nModified Nissan GT-Rs have competed in time attack challenges, specially for WTAC (World Time Attack Challenge). Time attack GT-Rs have been fielded by [[HKS]], [[Precision Automotive Racing]] and [[LYFE]].\n\nIn 2015, the HKS's GT-R became as the fastest time attack GT-R, it has the same [[VR38DETT]] engine generating over 1200 whp. It's became the fastest vehicle at Fontana, California, [[Fuji Speedway]] (with a peak speed of over 322 km/h (200 mph) and in [[Sydney Motorsport Park]]. the car compete at the 2015 WTAC and won the GT-R R35 class with a fastest lap record of 1:30.838 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.speedhunters.com/2015/08/the-worlds-fastest-gt-r-hks-gt1000-plus/|title=The World's Fastest GT-R|date=2015-08-01|website=Speedhunters|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> But in 2017, LYFE's 1136 whp GT-R broke all HKS's records and won the title as fastest time attack GT-R at the WTAC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ksl.com/article/43215481/slc-company-builds-worlds-fastest-time-attack-racing-nissan-gt-r|title=SLC company builds world's fastest time attack racing Nissan GT-R|website=www.ksl.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 WTAC, Precision Automotive Racing's GT-R, driven by Aaron McGranahan, set a peak speed of 269 km/h (167 mph) and won the Flying 500 class title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldtimeattack.com/index.php/2017-results/|title=Full Results for the 2017 Yokohama World Time Attack Challenge Sydney.|website=World Time Attack Challenge Sydney|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n===Hill Climb===\n\nThe Nissan GT-R has competed in both stock and modified forms in many hill climbing competitions, such as the [[Jaguar Simola Hill Climb]] in South Africa.\n\nAt the 2019 Jaguar Simola Hill Climb, the Nissan GT-R was named the most successful supercar. In the final Top 10 Shootout event, Kyle Mitchell won the event, setting a time of 40.862 seconds and becoming the fastest road-legal vehicle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/motoring/motorsport/super-wing-nissan-gt-r-crowned-king-of-the-hill-in-knysna-22685762|title='Super wing' Nissan GT-R crowned King of the Hill in Knysna|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.wheels24.co.za/Motorsport/Jaguar_Simola_Hillclimb/nissan-gt-r-wins-at-the-jaguar-simola-hillclimb-20190506|title=WATCH: #OMGTR - Nissan wins at the Jaguar Simola Hillclimb|date=2019-05-06|website=Wheels|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n===Drifting===\n\nIn February 2016, using a modified GT-R NISMO, [[Masato Kawabata]] set a new world record for the fastest 30-degree drift at approximately 304&nbsp;km/h at the [[Fujairah International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.drive.com.au/motor-news/nissan-sets-fastest-ever-drift-record-20150128-go1i2p.html|title=Nissan sets fastest ever drift record|last1=Tripolone|first1=Dom|date=3 October 2016|website=Drive|language=en-au|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\n\nThe Nissan GT-R played a main role in ''[[Fast & Furious 6]]''.<ref name=\"MW2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motorward.com/2013/01/fast-and-furious-6-nissan-gt-r-revealed/|title=Fast and Furious 6 Nissan GT-R Revealed|editor-last=Barari|editor-first=Arman|publisher=Motorward|accessdate=January 21, 2013}}</ref> The car in the widely successful movie has modified bumpers, new vented hood, modified fenders, side sills, carbon doors, carbon roof, and carbon spoilers.\n\nOn the August 13, 2014, Mike Newman broke the record for the 'fastest speed for a car driven blindfolded' in a Nissan GT-R modified by Litchfield Motors (UK).<ref>{{Cite book|last=Glenday|first=Craig|title=Guinness World Records 2016|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-910561-01-0|location=|pages=97|quote=|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year!!Award and Title\n|-\n|2007||''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]]'' Awards \u2013 Sports car of the Year<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.topgear.com/content/timetoburn/sections/galleries/other/awards07/12/ |title=TopGear Galleries \u2013 TG Awards '07 |accessdate=January 17, 2008 |author=Jason Barlow}}</ref>\n|-\n|2008||''[[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]]'' \u2013 Drivers Car of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.nissan.co.jp/GT-R/R35/0710/ |title=\u65e5\u7523\uff1aNISSAN GT-R [GT-R &#93; \u30b9\u30dd\u30fc\u30c4\uff06\u30b9\u30da\u30b7\u30e3\u30ea\u30c6\u30a3/SUV Web\u30ab\u30bf\u30ed\u30b0 \u30db\u30fc\u30e0 |publisher=.nissan.co.jp |accessdate=November 20, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928195909/http://www2.nissan.co.jp/G